3 Chapter 1: Introduction
Thank you for exploring this Introduction to From Zero to Pro UX & Accessibility Designer in 1 
month. One of the great takeaways I carry with me from Simon Sinek is this idea to Always 
start with the why. It is a basic but challenging question when som eone needs something, like 
in this field, when a software company needs some sort of development from a UX designer if 
they do not have a clear enough why, then it will be an extremely challenging how for the 
designer. What is User Experience? Figure: A Person or People who are users having experience Great UX (User Experience) 
 
User Experience (UX) is.. 
4 All interactions that a user has with a product, and the ideas, emotions, and memories 
that those moments create. How a user feels when they use (interact with) a product. How it is perceived, learned, 
and used. The practice of designing a product with user in mind. Multi disciplinary approach. When we talk about user experience (UX), we need to talk about why. We have come a long 
way in the last 20 years; in terms of software development, what used to take ten people to do 
can now often be done by one. Now, we have grown even beyond that. In a ddition to 
expediency, we now need to consider the user experience. It is not just if the software has 
functionality: Success also depends on making things easy. The expectation for the user is a 
seamless experience. There are three major components of any software application or system: 
UX, security, and performance. If there is a challenge in the UX, the application, website, or 
service will struggle regardless of whether it has security and performance. It needs all three 
legs to stand. Figure: Three m ajor aspects of any Software 

5 In practice, we have also seen solid UX and performance, but due to weak security, we 
read about companies with data breaches all the time. Security encompasses privacy and 
personalization that has been entrusted to a company, which puts the consumer at risk when 
data is stolen. When this occurs, companies lose their credibility with the public, and they often 
must go to great expense to rebuild their reputation. What about issues with performance? Let 
us say an application or s oftware exists within 4G networks that will soon migrate to 5G, where 
everything will function at a much faster pace. If that is the case, the performance of the 
application is going to be expected to be as fast. Even if it is not as fast, user expectation will be 
that processing timeframes will be communicated users need feedback that the application is 
processing information. The job of the UX professional is to take an awful experience, that a user might rank as a 0/5, 
and negate the problems to creat e positive interaction, a 5/5. So, what exactly is UX? It is not 
just the ideas, emotions, and memories that interactions with software create it is also the 
feelings and satisfaction that become associated with your brand in the real world as well. Thin k 
about positive experiences you may have had with a car brand or dealer. If the companys 
product has been dependable and your experiences with the dealership have built trust, then 
you will have loyalty to them when it comes to your next purchase. Conver sely, if there is a bad 
moment, let us say with a cellphone or a cell provider, with a faulty product or unfair billing, 
those moments will be stored in the consumers mind when it comes to upgrading a device or 
choosing a new company. 
6 Figure 1. A UX P rofessionals job is to take the product UX from 0 to 5 
 
The exact definition of UX, as outlined by the International Organization for Standardization, is a 
persons perceptions and responses resulting from the use and/or anticipated use of a product, 
system, or service. Beyond that, it is not just the use of these things, but also the anticipation of 
said items. Think of the hype that often surrounds the release of a new iPhone it is because of 
the loyalty in their fanbase that customers get excited about the hardware and software featur es 
that are due to come out.

Each added choice should 
be justified because each added choice also raises the level of friction for the user. Figure 10. Myth 5: The need for many options 
 
Having choices is considered a good thing. We are used to choices, and we value de arly if we 
can be in control. However, the more choices a website or web application offers, the harder it is 
to understand the interface. Studies show that having too many options often leads to decision 
paralysis and frustration. As a rule , people only v alue an abundance of features before they 
start using the given product. After they have started using it, the simpler solution wins 
with higher satisfaction . Current psychological theory and research affirm the positive affective and motivational 
consequences of having personal choice. These findings have led to the popular notion that the 
more choice, the better that the human ability to manage, and the human desire for, choice is 
unlimited. Findings from 3 experimental studies starkly challenge this implicit assumption that 
having more choices is necessarily more intrinsically motivating than having fewer. These 
experiments, which were conducted in both field and laboratory settings, show that people are 
more likely to purchase gourmet jams or chocolates or to undertake optional class essay 

37 assignments when offered a limited array of 6 choices rather than a more extensive array of 24 
or 30 choices. Moreover, pa rticipants reported greater subsequent satisfaction with their 
selections and wrote better essays when their original set of options had been limited. Implications for future research are discussed [Ref:10] . Simplicity is key to great and innovative product design. But simplicity (reduction of complexity) 
is way often confused with minimalist style (reduction of elements). In fact, simple looking, 
minimal product UIs often carry hidden complexity. Design decisions aiming for reduction can easily introduce more friction and cognitive load, 
leading to a more complex user experience. Icons without text labels are difficult to understand, 
nonstandard gestures provide no obvious affordance, the minimalist hamburger menu was 
proven many times to perform poorly. We should all strive for simplicity, but we must make sure not to oversimplify for the sake of 
minimalism. As Albert Einstein put it, Everything should be made as simple as possible, but not 
simpler. 
38 Myth 6 is to give users what they wa nt immediately. The UX designer must first give users what 
they need so that they can be successful with what they want. The user doesnt necessarily 
know what they are asking if it is logical or even feasible, so an experienced UX designer 
scaffolds the experience, so the user has what is needed to achieve what is wanted. Figure 11. Myth 6: Giving users what they want 
Myth 7 is that usability is greater than beauty. They both are important so solutions that 
succeed at both are best. Figure 12. Myth 7: Usability is greater than beauty 
 

39 Myth 8 is to copy what works for others. It works for them because they have researched their 
product with their users it is not a one sizefitsall. Absolutely, find inspiration or incorporate 
aspects of others successes, but UX is not just plug andplay. Does Googles single search bar 
come close to your needs? Or does Amazons mega menu with its millions of products translate 
to your offerings? Simply copying another can lead to oversimplification or overkil l! 
40 Figure 13. Myth 8: Copy what works for others 
Myth 9 is that UX is simply a project step. UX is a continuous journey there should be a UX 
designer when a product is being discussed through to after its launch. What if at the beginning 
stages a UX designer can see that an existing product can be modified and thereby eliminate 
the need for an entirely new product? Consider the efficiency and cost savings! Money is saved 
on design and development and will cost only a fraction on re investi ng. Theres an important 
lesson here, that the UX designer is not just about design the role is also about being efficient 
and problem solving, even if that translates into not having to design a new product at all! It 
might be useful to see the UX desig ner as a strategist as well. There are some specific pitfalls to avoid in order to achieve great UX design.

For one, a web 
application or software program should never look like an Excel spreadsheet thats what Excel 
spreadsheets are for! Second, techni cal errors, like 404 errors that hold no meaning to the user 
are a disaster; great effort needs to go into avoiding these issues. The third pitfall is 
unintentionally forcing users to think about the behind the scenes functionality of a program or 
proces s, whether it is related to how the software operates or the ordering and organization of 
an office. The fourth pitfall is a messy user interface, such as too many icons in a word 
processing program. A successful user interface is efficient, not cluttered. Fifth is simply bad 
design such as colors having no meaning or purpose, clutter, and unreadable text. The sixth 
pitfall is catering to super users or expert users, those users of higher demand and 
sophistication beyond the typical user. This can delay t he launching of a product or 
overcomplicate the interface for standard users when other options such as specialized, 
separate screens might work better. In fact, giving access to additional functions to the group 
that demands or requires them can foster mo re loyalty to a brand. Seventh is trying to address 
all edge cases upfront. Of course, there are always going to be some issues, problems, and 
friction with any product or application. The question is one of frequency. If one addresses the 
41 most common 40% of potential questions, the rare 60% of potential questions can be resolved 
at a more reasonable and feasible rate. The challenge is the change. What happens if there is no change? Bottom line: a company can 
get replaced. Think about the extent that Kodak has vanished for not changing along with the 
digital economy. Despite warning signs and competitor advancements, the need for change was 
not heeded and cost the entire company. Change is constant in every company and every 
industry, and, therefore, all mus t adapt. UX designers are the proponents of change. People like 
to be the same; they dont like to change; they dont like to have to learn a new, different way of 
doing things. To become a successful UX practitioner, one must be willing to push and 
challe nge, choosing battles wisely to make progress. Figure 14. Challenge is change 
Myth 10: Success happens overnight 
The Apple iPod instantly turned the MP3 player market upside down, right? Amazon changed 
the book selling business like a shot, didnt it? Well, in fact they didnt. No matter how it may 
seem from the outside. 
42 The fact is that it takes many years to be an overnight success even for internet entrepreneurs. Years of hard work, endurance, learning, experimenting, and many failures along the wa y. And 
sometimes pursuing a project almost everybody dislikes, like developing Gmail with its crazy 
Javascript stuff . Seemingly swift successes that took a long time to achieve: 
Twitter : Twitter founder Biz Sto ne had been creating blogging, mobile and social 
products for 8 years before founding Twitter. He says: Timing, perseverance, and ten 
years of trying will eventually make you look like an overnight success. Timing 
Lessons 
Another account on Twitter: The Non Overni ght Success: How Twitter Became Twitter 
Apple iPod : It took 3 years for the iPod to become an overnight success. The first iPod 
was released in 2001. Within a year, Apple had revised it to improve ergonomics in a 
second version. But it wasnt until the fo urth version in 2004 that sales started to take 
off. Apples Overnight Success! , originally disc ussed in Bill Buxtonss brilliant 
book Sketching User Experiences . 
37signals : When we launched Basecamp five years ago, I thin k we had less than 2,000 
people subscribed to our RSS feed. Add a few thousand more who were just checking 
the site manually and its probably reasonable to guess that our initial audience was 
below 5,000 people. By todays standards, thats tiny! And that audience had even taken a few years to 
build. Overnight success takes years 
Gmail : We started working on Gmail in Aug ust 2001. For a long time, almost everyone 
disliked it.

[…] Quite a few people thought that we should kill the project, or perhaps 
"reboot it as an enterprise product with native client software, not this crazy Javascript 
43 stuff. Even when we got to the po int of launching it on April 1, 2004 – two and a half 
years after starting work on it – many people inside of Google were predicting doom. Overnight success takes a long time 
Amazon : It launched in 1994, but only added book reviews in 1996 and CDs in 1998. And lets not forget that they werent profitable in the first seven years. Many startups: despite all the "you can also do it blogposts, many startups tell you 
how long it took them to get the first 100 customers and how much endurance you need 
to become profitable. Theres No Myth, Only Years Of Hard Work , Bootsrapping a 
Company , Lessons Learned from 5 Years of SaaS 
Angry Birds : The mobile game Angry Birds was a huge success. But Rovio had been 
through 50 mobile games up to that point and almost went bankrupt (tl;dr version ) 
FedEx : Frederick W. Smiths idea for an express delivery service was born in 1965, 
FedEx launched in 1973 (with only 7 packages on the first day), in the first 26 months in 
business, it made a loss of $29 million, and only by the late 1970s did it become a 
success. Frederick W. Smith: No Overnight Success and FedEx Corporation: The 
Creation of Overnight Air express Ind ustry 
The Beatles : The Beatles seemed to burst onto the scene with a string of #1 hits and 
an appearance on the Ed Sullivan show in 1964. But they had been playing small clubs 
in Liverpool and Hamburg since 1957, and while they had mass appeal early on, t heir 
first great critical success, Sgt. Peppers, was released in 1967. Overnight Success: It 
Takes Yea rs, see also Malcolm Gladwells book Outliers with a detailed account. or take Tiger Woods : Although he was the youngest golfer who won the Masters, 
hed been practicing golf practically his whole life, he was a child prodigy, introduced to 
golf before the age of two. Tiger Woods (Wikipe dia) 
44 More on the idea of instant success: 
The notion of overnight success is very misleading and rather harmful to any hope for 
long term and sustainable growth in this industry. […] whatever the business, big 
success takes years to build and there are ve ry few counter examples. says Spotify co 
founder Daniel Ek . Overnight success takes a long time. To quote Daft Punk work it 
harder, make it better, do it faster, makes us stronger, more than ever, hour after hour, 
our work is never over. Seth Godin argues that Along the way, some people have trained themselves to believe 
that the only kind of success worth having is overnight success. That if you dont hit #1 
the first week, youve failed. That if your interface isnt perfect out of the box, or if you 
dont get 5,000 people standing in line at the opening of your new store, youve failed. Barrie Bergman writes in his ChangeThis manifesto that Personally, Ive never met an 
overnight success. Ive met people whove done something well for a long time and were 
suddenly discovered. Then everyone assumed they came out of nowhere, that their 
fame happened overnight. Overnight success is really overnight expos ure. says Jonathan Fields . Oh, and yes, YouTube is quite an exception. Though it did take 5 years even for them to turn 
profitable. Myth #31: UX design is a step in a project 
Many think that user experience design is confined to sketching the interfaces. However, UX 
design is a much broader process that ideally starts at the strategy level and affects the 
whole lifecyc le of a project or a business. 
45 UX design begins by learning about the business model, doing user research and 
understanding how a service can fit into the users lives in a meaningful way. Thus UX design 
has a crucial part in defining the business strategy , providing baselines for business decisions 
with such design deliverables as personas or user stories.

A UX driven process doesnt end 
with the UIs either, its also about testing with people, supporting development, making ongoing 
adjustments even after the launch. How UX design is way more than user interface design: 
Interface is a component of user experience, but theres much more. Peter Merholz 
Ive had clients tell me not to worry about what their strategy is, because why would a 
designer care a bout that? UX is more than just skin deep. Dan Saffer 
User experience design isnt a checkbox; you dont do it and then move on. It needs to 
be integrated into everything you do. Liz Danzico 
 from 10 Most Common Misconceptions About User Experience Design . In Design Is a Process, Not a Methodolo gy at UXmatters, Pabini Gabriel Petit shows the 
steps of a complete product design process, chunked to three phases: discovery, design 
and development support. UI design / wireframing is only a step in the 8 step process. The many different activities of u sercentered design is well demonstrated by 
the Generic Work Process , listing 100+ techniques and methods that can be used in UX 
design. Jesse James Garrett defines five planes of UX design starting from strategy level to the 
concrete UI The Elements of User Experience: simple version (PDF) , detailed version 
(PDF) 
That Sq uiggle of the Design Process visually shows how research and prototyping are 
essential and move the design process from the abstract to the final design. 
46 The book A Project Guide to UX Design details the steps of UX design from defining the 
user experience (i.e. project objectives, business requirements, research, personas) to 
designing for the user experience (site maps, wireframes, usability testing, post launch 
activities). 
47 Chapter 2 
 
This chapter will be covering the most important criteria of design principles in the UX field. Failure to consider design principles when we are designing anything means missing crucial 
components, like trying to make a hamburger but forgetting the patty. When you look at any 
highly successful product, it is easy to see how certain design principles have been intentionally 
considered and applied. Take the iRobot: Such an easy touse product with one main button 
that starts its cleaning cycle. When there is a problem, some models will now tell you, stopping 
and calling out that the bin is full, for instance. If the battery is low, it will return to its base to 
recharge. The ease and convenience far outpace any conventional vacuum where you do the 
work. How i t functions is an achievement in itself, but there is also a companion mobile app to 
start, stop, and keep tabs on the iRobots progress. These are amazing elements of design principles that are so user friendly that people using the 
product love it and ev en become emotionally attached! We discussed emotional friction in the 
previous chapter, one of three types of friction, including cognitive and physical. The goal of a 
UX designer is to reduce all three kinds of friction. The iRobot has been so successful because 
it has reduced emotional friction to such a low level that people can become attached to it being 
in their house it eases the burden of a tedious chore and frees up time and energy for its 
owner. There are challenges that these design principles will solve. Depending on your medium, such 
as print or digital space, there are relevant principles that must be considered for success. Consider a website that must entail everything from the contrast between the text and 
background to the accessibility of functions that would be important to a client. For a charity 
relying on donations, there should be no hindrance to finding that donate button. It must 
always be a consideration of how the human brain tends to function when encountering design 
48 to facil itate ease of use and to lower any obstacles to a clients objectives in reaching an 
audience and achieving any desired call to action. When we understand the different stages and 
levels of human cognition, such as interpreting and grasping information, we can then try to tap 
into those abilities with our design. In that sense, honoring design principles can limit ambiguity 
and confusion by acknowledging the limitations of human interpretation. Figure 15. Representation of brain and its components 
Human visual processing has evolved through several stages.

The eye is connected to the optic 
nerve, which leads to the brain. The retina receives the images which are registered by the 
macula, sent to the brain to interpret. Stage 1 of human visual processing i s central vision, 
where you can focus on a particular text or information, which happens in microseconds. We 
become quite efficient all the way back to childhood with pattern recognition as we at first do not 
understand what we are seeing. Patterns of cert ain people, such as parents or siblings, 
constantly re occur, leading to recognition. There is a huge amount of learning in the first years 
of life where one starts to recognize colors, shapes, and objects. Thats all incorporated into 
memory, where your b rain has it stored for access to help with interpretation. Perceptions from 
sight, sound, smell, touch they all persist and form our memories, so that, for instance, as 

49 adults, we wont touch a pressure cooker knowing that it is hot and will burn us. The amygdala 
in the back of the brain acts as a panic button to help us avoid these kinds of dangers. As UX 
designers, we want to avoid mistakes that will cause alarm or a threat to security; the goal is to 
make users feel safe and secure with ease of use. The second stage is called pre attentive processing, which occurs in the subconscious mind. Many of us have experienced driving home from work along a typical route where we were just 
on auto pilot. We can be actively thinking about a project or a design w hile at the same time we 
are perceiving visual cues that guide us home. The conscious mind is turning over a problem 
while the subconscious mind is getting us to our houses. While it is better to pay close attention 
to the road, we often fall into this pat tern due to repetition and familiarity. Of course, road work 
or an accident will often pull the subconscious to the conscious so that we can be mindful and 
more attentive to a more dangerous situation. The brain will make the switch automatically, 
often re gardless of what has become the primary task. Stage three is attentive processing which is what is occurring in the conscious mind. Reading 
this book right now is attentive processing, and understanding what the words on the page are 
communicating is a t the forefront of your mind. If you were eating on the side, much of the 
eating might be happening subconsciously, until you spill or drop something on the book, 
keyboard, or your lap. No one is truly multitasking because at the milli second scale the foc us is 
switching back and forth from conscious to subconscious. So at these three stages, the central 
region wants to grasp essential information as quickly and efficiently as possible in its 
interpretation. The brain does this incredibly well as it looks t o define and identify what the eyes 
are perceiving. The first thing the brain does is to attempt to see boundaries and shapes, clearly 
defined edges, to better process what is being viewed. It doesnt necessarily have to be in color 
as long as these other factors are readily identifiable. Issues like blurriness or lack of contrast 
are a disturbance to this process. 
50 Once central vision determines edges, it can then discern shapes and patterns within those 
boundaries, which is part of pre attentive processing . This then progresses to attentive 
processing which is much keener and focused. Pre attentive processing may misinterpret an 
image based on preconceived ideas, whereas attentive processing may allow for closer 
inspection and will then rectify the misunder standing. For instance, the edges and curves of an 
object on the ground may initially be interpreted as a snake, causing alarm in the amygdala; 
however, upon closer inspection of texture and the opposing ends of the object shows it to be a 
hose. In this ca se, the attentive processing overrides the conclusion of pre attentive processing. Designing should allow for seamless processing from central vision to conscious processing 
without having to pay too much attention. Having to pay too much attention to the apps or 
interfaces we are designing will cause friction in the mind of the user, making the design less 
effective. There are stages in design where the goal is to catch the attention of the user, which is when 
we use special attention getting elements that are deliberately introduced. The user should be 
on auto pilot in pre attentive processing but not inattentive processing.

A dictionary definition for 
design principles would be as follows: In order to better understand how human perception 
works, Gestalt psychologists proposed a number of laws of perceptual organization, including 
the laws of similarity, Pragnanz, proximity, continuity, and closure. The strength of this 
definition is the list of laws of which any UX designer should have a firm grasp in o rder to be 
successful. These are the go to principles for any interface design, no matter how large or 
small. 
51 Key UX design principles include Fitts Law; Pareto Principle 80/20; Hicks Law; and Gestalts 
Principles of Proximity, Continuity, Closure, and F igure Ground. Fitts Law is a scientific law 
(which) predicts that the time required to rapidly move to a target area is a function of the ratio 
between the distance to the target and the width of the target. In a nutshell, this describes the 
accuracy wi th which someone can move a mouse cursor from a point on the screen to the 
intended target; there is a relationship between the distance the cursor must move and the 
width of the target. The bigger the target, the easier to spot, and the closer the cursor, the more 
accurate the user can move the cursor to the target. Even from 10 15 years ago, everything 
from drop down menus to buttons has increased in size and been made more mobile friendly to 
help with accuracy. Consider the growing commonality of touch t echnology any button or field 
should be larger than the fingertip so that single fields can be accurately selected. It is not 
advisable to use smaller text boxes or buttons as we cannot assume touch is only for mobile 
larger devices like tablets and ev en laptops are regularly used with touch technology. 
52 Figure 16. The Fitts Law 
The Pareto Principle is the 80/20 rule, that 80% of the effects of any given process come from 
20% of the effort put into it. This is similar to a productivity principle you may have heard of in 
the past, that 80% of the work is done by 20% of the people . Here, 80% of the effects of any 
given process or system that is being developed is from 20% of the effort. In terms of 
functionality, whats used 80% of the time took 20% of the time to build out. The rest of the time, 
80%, was spent on the functionality thats used 20% of the time by advanced and super users. This has similarities with anything that we are going to design. We focus on 20% that delivers 
80% of the features and value. Users then will back you on the remaining 20%, giving you the 
time neede d for more development. In the UX context, it is like saying 80% of users use 20% of 
features so we focus on what matters most; once you focus on this and do it well, the rest of 
the product will slowly fall into place. The last 20% is going to be much m ore challenging 
because of the advanced features and edge cases you will need to develop. Figure 17. The Pareto Principle 
 

53 Hicks Law says that the time it takes to make a decision increases with the number and 
complexity of options. Imagine a drop down menu of cities in the world that tens of thousands 
of choices. Lets say we narrowed it down to United States cities thats still a tremendous 
number for a dropdown. What about looking at just a state, like California, which has over 400 
alone. What sense would it make for someone to have to skim over 400 choices to locate a city 
in California? A text box where once the type is entered starts giving options is a more logical 
solution. What a better user experience! Google does this with search terms once a few 
characters are entered. A three minute search can possibly be narrowed to three seconds. As 
the number of options increases, the time to locate an option increases. This is where desi gners come into the picture and create smart text boxes or smart drop down 
menus. The best number is seven in a drop down option, but going beyond seven means an 
increase in time and lower user experience. The exception would be well known, patterned 
information, like states in a nation that users are familiar with these cases are quickly 
navigated.

Otherwise, we begin to see categories and logical classifications to reduce time 
spent searching for a particular term or product. Consider remote controls of the past, especially 
when they had to encompass VCRs and/or DVDs as well as channel numbers, types of input, 
and connected systems then compare those with simplified remotes for devices like the Apple 
TV, which has basically three buttons and directiona l arrows. The learning curve is minimal due 
to its efficiency. Reduction of complexity is even felt physically as the eyes relax and cognitive 
friction is lessened. Hicks Law is also for the complexity of information in terms of how 
something is structure d, organized, and even colored. 
54 
Figure 18. Hicks Law 
We have discussed human visual processing in terms of stage one being central vision, stage 
two being subconscious, and stage three being attentive, conscious processing. Gestalt design 
principles co me from stage two. Here is where the design seems basic and friendly because 
you are not trying to get someones conscious attention, just subconscious attention, and 
reactions. The focus here is grouping, edges, shapes, objects, and colors. Conscious 
interpretations can override the perceptions from stage two, which actually can correct initial 
misinterpretations. Our goal is to design into stage two to make things seem as easy as 
possible, as seamless as possible, as friendly as possible. Overdesigning a button, for instance, 
is wasting time as people are used to the shape and functionality of a button. It reminds me of the topic of biophilia, the human preference for the biological green of plants, 
bushes, grasses, and trees. When we think of white space in design, and the feeling of room 
and openness, it is similar to the typical response to a wide open field, plane, or steppe theres 
a feeling of awareness and safety. Savannah preference is a term that captures this as well, 
that the savannah enviro nment is quite appealing to human beings. Design is supposed to bring 
that same kind of feeling to the user experience. 
55 
Figure 19. Hicks Law example: remote control 
 
A principle also to understand is Gestalts Similarity, where objects with shared vis ual 
characteristics are automatically taken to be related. Similar colors and/or similar shapes can 
help someone categorize, count, group, and interpret information. These choices must 
communicate similarities in meaning, or interpretation will be challeng ing and cognitive friction 
will be an issue. Combining shape and color with text brings more clarity to those who can 
recognize all three, but also give access to someone who is, say, colorblind. 
56 Figure 20. Gestalts Similarity 
Another design principle is that of Proximity, which is when different elements are laid out close 
together, so they are perceived to be of the same group. This could be in rows, columns, or 
other groupings, all depending on the spacing between the objects. This particularly comes into 
play when mixing any text with images: Text needs to be close in proximity to the image or 
object it describes or is tied to. The Related principle is similar but actually overrides proximity. Similar shapes side by side would look like rows if they differed from the shapes above and 
below, even if the spacing would dictate interpretation as a column if all the shapes were the 
same. The principle also can apply with contrasting colors or sizes, regardless of whether the 
shape is the same or not. This is important in design because related patterns can break 
proximity patterns if necessary. 
57 Figure 21. Gestalts Proximity 
Violations within a pattern are also a design principle of the note. A different color, shape, or 
size in a pattern will immediate ly gain the attention of the user it pulls the view from stage two 
to stage three, demanding attentive processing. In designing violations, as with other design 
principles, it is crucial to keep in mind color blind individuals who may need shape or size clues 
in order to draw their attention. A combination of shape and color, two elements of design, can 
be even more effective for your typical user. 
58 Figure 22.

Violations  
Gestalts Continuity principle speaks to how the human brain can interpret entire shapes from 
partial information the brain will fill in missing information to suggest a complete image. You 
can make four circles that are spaced apart seem as though a r ectangle is partially covering ¼ 
of each circle simply by removing a slice out of each circle to show the corners of a rectangle. The mind doesnt need to see an entire line or side of a rectangle, just the indication of one. Just 
like when we see two pa ths curving toward each other but their meeting point is blocked by 
plants our brain fills in that information, and we assume there is actually one continuous path 
even though we have no visual proof. The Gestalts principle of continuity is used by desig ners 
who fade out a block of text the perception is that there is more text than is being shown, 
tipping off the user to look for a way to scroll to further material. 
59 Figure 23. Gestalts Continuity 
The final design principle we are going to cover is Gutenbergs Diagram, which dictates that 
when there are four corners of information, the way users proceed to visually interpret is from 
the left top corner diagonally to the right bottom corner. The bottom left and upper right receives 
less focus due to t his natural eye tracking. Now you see why so many logos and icons are on 
the upper left of websites. Save, next, and cancel buttons are the bottom right due to this 
principle as well. As you might expect, this flows in the opposite direction for countries that read 
from right to left. Figure 24. Gutenbergs Diagram 
As a designer, our goal is to be able to effectively reach a wide range of users in a wide range 
of contexts. Some users use many applications and must be highly mobile, why at the other end 
of the spectrum are those who use relatively few applications and have little need for m obility. Understanding these design principles helps guide design to be tailored to common user types 
and needs. 
60 Chapter 3 
 
Planning is key. We can start thinking through user experience with preliminary sketching, just 
having ideas down on paper. We must think through each user segment, meaning the 
experience of a regular user, superuser, admin user whatever profile you can imagine 
engaging with the product. Each journey of a user needs to be mapped out, from landing 
pages to navigating through any process the product entails. Every stage of the process must 
be carefully designed and thought through multiple instances of what happens as the user 
navigates through to the end goal, whether thats to fill out a form, place an order, evaluate 
learning, e tc. This mapping out of the experience helps consider usability enhancements as well. For 
instance, consider the typical checkout screen. How many have you encountered that include 
the option to save for later, such as Amazon? This is an appealing opti on consider mobile 
users who might not be in a place to complete the checkout process. It causes cognitive and 
emotional friction to have gone through the process of filling out user information such as email 
and addresses only to not be able to save tha t information for later if the purchase is not 
immediately possible. These potential functionalities can be thought through in the early 
mapping. Three aspects and subsequent questions must be considered for the options being mapped out 
for inclusion. One is desirability will people want it? This isnt just for an end purpose, but also 
for the functionality of the system being designed. When we talk about a save for later 
function, for instance, we can see there would be a definite desire for some user s in some 
contexts. Second, then, is viability, which is the question of whether the client can make money 
with it. Again, save for later is centered on retaining customers and garnering a potential 
purchase in the future. If a user can pick right up whe re he or she left off on a purchase, 
wouldnt we expect the customer to return, versus someone who would have to start from 
61 scratch with an empty shopping cart? Lastly is feasibility if certain functionality is desired, can 
I deliver it? In other words , can the software or hardware handle the process? There are three criteria to consider, then, when it comes to usability.

Is it intuitive? How easy is 
it for the user to understand without aid or instruction? This area implements design principles 
such a s Fricks Law, like the size of a button reducing the time to identify and click it. This leads 
to the second criteria: efficiency. How quickly can information be interpreted and acted upon? These two in concert lead to the third criteria, which is satisfa ction: The feeling of the user that 
the process was simple and worked well. These three components ultimately make the 
processor software usable. Usability is not just about the design something beautiful in its 
appearance does not necessarily equate to a solid design. Figure 25. Usability 
   There are many beautiful things that thoroughly lack functionality. You can have a 
breathtakingly gorgeous teapot, but if the spigot isnt on the right side, it is impossible to use! When you have individuals from the graphics industry coming into use r experience, it is 
important to not just get caught up in a great looking product, visually appealing images, or 
amazing icons and fail in usability tasks. If people dont know what a function is for or how to 
use it, it doesnt matter how pretty the ic on looks. It is a misunderstanding that a graphic 
designer automatically translates into being able to create a product that is ultimately usable. 
62 Without considering intuitiveness, efficiency, and satisfaction, you could end up with a very 
beautiful softw are teapot. Mapping is a great usability exercise to determine how functional a product or process is for the 
user. Think about a cooking range with four burners and an oven underneath. How would you 
design or layout the five dials on a control panel so that use of the stove would be intuitive and 
efficient? Or how about communicating to a user wherein the process of going from computer to 
router to connect to the internet there is a problem? Mapping thinks through the best potential 
design options to ac hieve usability. Usability makes the user experience better. It is useful to think through a multi leveled development process, starting with utility, that the 
product is useful and meets needs. This is the starting point. Then comes the aspect of 
functio nality that people need to be able to see, the more easily the better. At this point, the 
appeal becomes important, that the consumer likes the way the product looks and feels: 
tactically and visually there is satisfaction for the user. These work towards developing the 
brand experience, where, in an abstract sense, there are positive feelings associated with the 
brand. If you consider the revolutionary development of the iPhone that took a basic cell phone 
focused on utility and elevated the usability to d esirability that created a brand experience 
phenomenon, you can see this development process in action. That isnt to say that utility is ever neglected the core is often still the driver. If your phone, for 
instance, loses the ability to call and text, it severely cripples its value and the user experience. All of the additional functionalities might be present, but without the core, then the entire system 
collapses. This goes back to the point of providing needs first: Wants are secondary. The utility 
is the survival mode of any product. If the utility is in any way degraded or non functional, the 
trust in the entire system is going to fall apart. 
63 Aesthetic Usability Effect is a phenomenon where users believe that beautiful software is more 
usable. T wo similar software with a little color change, one more appealing visually than the 
other, lent to the idea that colors equated to better software. This was despite the same 
functionality and usability of the two choices. Yes, color is vitally important. Any corporate 
website you view has been carefully designed down to the color scheme they know even if 
they have a perfectly functioning interface, an unappealing color scheme will repel users. Figure 26. Aesthetic Usability Effect is when users believ e that beautiful software is more usable 
What can be done for improvement? It is really by keeping the aspects of the user experience at 
the forefront of the mind during development. It is a cross section of areas, including research, 
usability, informati on architecture, interaction design, visual design, and content.

If you are 
working for a company that has not invested in UX/CX/PX/SX (user experience, customer

the advantages of such an investment. Some examples from studies show that moving from 
below average UX to above average would yield additional annual revenue. We have seen

creating capabilities and user interface. User experience is only going to grow because it is a

66 UX Design Approaches 
Wireframing 
Wireframing is one way to approach user experience design. Wireframing is drawing screen 
mock ups for new systems so that a UX designer can quickly and effectively communicate 
design choices. There are wireframe tools for doing manual wireframes that are simple and 
easy to draw. Wireframing allows stakeholders to foresee how the new system being designed 
will look and function, making it an ideal tool for gathering early feedback that can, in turn, 
influence the design of the system. In the long run, this will save time later in the process by 
avoiding major revisions or iteratio ns. Often wireframes will lay out multiple options to assess 
which is most appealing to stakeholders. The approach is not to expect any of the options 
offered to clients to fit every need and expectation initially. The point is to allow feedback and 
involv e clients in the process. Figure 28. Examples of Wireframing 
It is never advisable to go in with only one option. It will set you up for failure. Multiple options 
not only push creativity and innovation by having to map out more than one process but als o 
helps you think about things in a different way. The client then also bears some responsibility as 
their feedback has guided development. As you present each option, you will get insight into 
what features are preferred. The moment you start presenting o ptions and show your 

67 investment, you increase trust with your clients.

More simply, user experience is how you feel about every interaction 
you have with what is in front of you know you are using it and how those interactions create 
memories that may stick with you for the long term in future s cenarios. It is important to qualify the desired results of UX. You want your users to be happy good news 
spreads fast, which leads to increased sales. To some extent, delighted customers are doing 
the marketing for you. Second, satisfaction is also key . Satisfied users have increased loyalty 
with fewer support requests. They have more positive ideas rather than complaining about 
issues, as they know you have delivered credible products and services consistently they have 
come to rely on them. Rather t han being adversarial, there is more of a chance they will be 
suggestive of improvements and features that, if they have traction among your users, can 
result in a better product. Third, we want users to be productive in that, they become your 
proponents , your MVPs (Most Valuable Proponents!), who strongly recommend your product or 
service. They can give you testimonials or references whether you are trying to reach a new 
client or a new market. Your users happiness, satisfaction, and productivity can be a 
tremendous asset to your success. 
7 Figure: Happy and Satisfied Users who become Most Valuable Propo nents 
 
What exactly is needed in UX to achieve these desired results? There are seven factors to 
consider: Is it usable? Is it useful? Is it desirable? Is it findable? Is it valuable? Is it credible? Is it 
accessible? If all of these have affirmative answers, clients experience the results they want. Some of the time, people have six out of seven, but completely miss accessibility, which is one 
of the reasons we will spend a good amount of time on this topic in this book, in addition to 
usability and user experience. Figure 2. Needed in UX to achieve desired results 
 
There are tremendous advantages to user experience design. For one, there wil l be financial 
savings in projects, products, and services due to a decrease in the cost of redevelopment of 
the seven factors we have covered because of negative user feedback those issues would 
have been anticipated in thinking through the user experie nce in advance. The design will go 
through iterations to make it usable, accessible, and user friendly before it reaches the 
customer. The initial investment in development will pay off year after year. User experience is 
sowing a seed and then taking care of it with water, sunlight, and nutrients, resulting in a much 
heartier and healthier plant. In the same way, investment in user experience is going to give a 
much stronger return on investment. 
8 If the expectation is instant results with a UX designer, t here may be frustration. There might be 
cases where a UX designer can address some usability issues and see some gains quickly; 
however, a UX designer needs to be afforded the opportunity to develop a product to a stage 
that exceeds the expectations of a c lient. The bottom line is that when user experience is taken 
into consideration, long term development costs are going to be reduced, and an organizations 
revenue is going to go up. While it is possible in rare cases, these two results do not usually 
happ en simultaneously, so the UX designer needs the patience to design and flesh out his or 
her ideas. For example, what if the UX designer has a potential of five ideas to meet a need? While it may seem like developing five different ideas to address a single request is overkill or a 
waste of time, not doing so has an enormous potential of incurring future costs. The expertise of 
a UX team can go through mockups and models, as well as interview stakeholders and potential 
users, determining the best aspects and features of each option to get the best design. Good UX design results in motivation to use whatever content has been developed. Regular 
engagement with reliable content fosters loyalty. Patience and perseverance in the initial stages 
afford more potentia l for developing loyalty in users in the long term picture. Loyalty increases

Your thoroughness makes you both expert and 
consultant in their eyes as you are able to fine tune the product based on their responses. Endtoend wireframing is a diagram that walks t hrough any process or software step 
bystep, almost like a flow chart, showing the various paths users can take as they interact with

68 Why user Wireframes? Fig: Wireframing a software for use in mobiles, tablets, and des ktops. A wireframe is a schematic, a blueprint, useful to help you and your programmers and designers 
think and communicate about the structure of the software or website you're building. The same screen can be built in a lot of different ways, but only a few of them will get your 
message across correctly and result in an easy touse software or website. Nailing down a 
good interface structure is possibly the most important part of designing software . Doing this work now, before any code is written and before the visual design is finalized , 
will save you lots of time and painful adjustment work later. More example of wireframing of 
software applications like web or mobile are showin below. 
69 
Why do wireframes look the way they do? Wireframes typically have an intentional low fidelity look and feel to them, for the following 
reasons. 
70 1. Wireframes make it clear that this is not the final design 
No one could mistake a wireframe for the final look and feel of your application. Low fidelity and 
few colors force you to focus on structure over details. There will be lots of time for visual design 
once the structure is finalized. 
2. Wireframes convey that "this is all up for discussion" 
The rough feel encourages discussion. We call it a look no one is afraid to criticize . Wireframes 
are quick to make, so don't be shy asking for feedback ! Each screen probably only took a few 
minutes to make; don't worry, dont mind doing them over from scratch. What matters the most 
at this point is the final ease of use, so going through a few iterations is normal and expected. 
3. Wireframes make it clear that no code has been written yet 
If your customer or stakeholder received some screens that looked like screenshots of the final 
app, instead of a wireframe, they m ight assume that all the code behind those screenshots had 
already been written. This is most often not the case. Wireframes don't have this danger. Getting started with wireframes : 
To get started with wireframing, In the later part of the book for the cha pter on Designing the 
Low Fidelity Wireframes gets you started from the basics leveraging the Balsamiq tool . With 
great power comes great responsibility. Just because wireframing tools make it easy to come up 
with user interfaces, it doesn't mean that creating good user interfaces is easy. Ten Principles of Effective Wireframes 
 
71 Guiding principles to help designers wireframe better and encourage the entire team to 
participate in the design process. Ever wonder how the companies you admire create great 
products? It is not the tools they use and it is not just their incredible UI designers or developers. It is the process and culture theyve cultivated around design.

Effective wireframes do much more than just show a picture of a user interface, they 
also facilitate discussion, promote alignment , and supply instructions for developers . The following are these 10 principles for teams that want help defining their own process for 
wireframing and designing successful products . They encourage the entire team to 
participate and serve to remind designers that wireframes aren't complete without participation 
from others. 
10 Principles of Effective UI Wireframes 
1. Demonstrate an understanding of the problem 
2. Focus on user needs 
3. Thoroughly explore solutions 
4. Dont show more detail than necessary 
5. Functional, not fanciful 
6. Follow UI design patterns 
7. Invite discussion 
8. Incorporate ideas from others 
9. Are easy to understand 
10. Validate the solution with users and team membe rs 
 
72 
 
Principle 1: Demonstrate an understanding of the problem 
Articulate the exact problem youre trying to solve and who it impacts. Show the current 
workflow and whats wrong with it. Helps designers set the context for their solution. Don't start designing until you're sure you know who you're designing for, what they care about, 
and how the existing system works. Helps teams see how the current system is not working. Get buy in by surfacing customer pain points and their impact on business metrics. 
73  
 
Principle 2: Focus on user needs 
Ensure that what you design addresses a problem real users face and care about. People want 
solutions, not products. Helps designers make sure they're solving a real problem. Remember to keep the users and their goals at hand. Write them as a note on your 
wireframe or in a notebook. Focusing on the user keeps you focused on solving the right 
problem. Helps teams empathize with users. When presenting work to stakeholders or clients, use your focus on user needs to build a 
shared understanding of the problems they encounter and how the design helps alleviate it. 
74  
Principle 3: Thoroughly explore solutions 
Push beyond the first few obvious ideas. Dont be afraid to go down unknown paths . Helps designers discover novel solutions. Wireframes are great for divergent exploration. Go broad. Real creative exploration requires 
leaps. Venture into the unknown even if it is not feasible. Expand the possibilities and youll find 
yourself incorporating some of those novel ideas into your product. Helps teams see the value in design. Show the team how exploration and divergent thinking takes separate ideas and creates 
somethin g entirely new from the best pieces of each. 
75  
 
Principle 4: Dont show more detail than necessary 
It is natural to focus on small details when designing. Dont get hung up on things that can be 
decided later. Helps designers stay focused only on what needs to be designed or fixed. Be deliberate about details. Too much will blur the focus on what really matters, too little will not 
properly communicate the intent of the design. Invites teams to give feedback throughout the process. Leave areas in your design undesigned, intentionally, to solicit input from others, or to even call 
out that not enough information is available to know what should be there. 
76 
 
Principle 5: Functional, not fanciful 
Remember to bring your ideas back to reality at some point. Design 
for usefulness , consistency , and implement ability . Helps designers focus on structure, user flow, and possible solutions. Stay in low fidelity if you can until you know you have the right structure and user flows in place. Once you do, you can move forward in confidence . Helps teams remember that the problem is the focus, not the UI. Wireframes are a great artifact to show the various ways you guide the user through a task or 
help them accomplish a goal. Leaving out details and interactions will allow them to see your 
solution more clearly. 
77 
Principle 6: Follow UI design patterns 
Learn when and how to use standard user interface controls and elements. Take inspiration 
from similar solutions. Helps designers create feasible and familiar solutions. There are established conventions in interface design.

Combined with design systems and 
libraries, they create the visual language of your product. Leverage these patterns within your 
wireframes to mock up new features or products and youll be able to jump right into code. Helps teams understand why patterns exist and how users b enefit from them. Design may seem mysterious to people outside your team. Educating them on why you 
are doing what you're doing will help them understand its importance. 
78 
 
Principle 7: Invite discussion 
Dont be afraid to keep your designs unfinished, especially where youre uncertain. This makes 
it easier for others to give input and build on your ideas . Helps designers get feedback and buy in. Share unfinished work. When presenting , use language like, it could be or a possible 
solution may be Wireframes are perfect for this. You cannot easily review a half designed 
highfidelity prototype and appropriately comment, because it feels too real to ignore the 
unfinished parts. Helps teams make sure everyone's voice is heard. Wiref rames are always in process. Intentionally leaving places not finished opens them up for 
input, inviting comments and critique. 
79 
 
Principle 8: Incorporate ideas from others 
When you get feedback , update your design accordingly. Integrate subject matter experts' 
knowledge of the problem, users, or technology. Helps designers generate better concepts and solutions. The ease and speed with which anyone can create a wireframe leaves no reason why youd 
create only one concept. Or that only a designer can do it. Open the wireframing of ideas to the 
whole group. Youll get more enthusiasm for the process and folks will know they had a part in 
the solution. Helps teams feel included in the design process. Design is a team sport. Listening and feeding of f each others ideas will result in more thought 
through solutions to the users problem. 
80 
Principle 9: Are easy to understand 
Take the extra step to make them readable by others. Use notes and arrows to highlight areas 
of the design that arent obvious to viewers . Helps designers make designs comprehensible. Use wireframes to turn the problem or solution into som ething visual that everyone can refer to, 
discuss, and build on. Inspires teams to communicate clearly outside of their silos. The goal of any good artifact is a shared understanding of either the problem or a possible 
solution. Encourage the team to make ideas visual and to share them around for feedback. 
81 
 
Principle 10: Validate the solution with users and team members 
Talk to stakeholders and make sure the final proposal solves the stated problem and can 
be built. Better to catch a mistake here than once coding starts. Gives designers confidence that their design addresses the problem. Use wireframes to show real users your concepts to ensure that your solution does what you 
intend before investing in the building and shipping of th e product. Encourages teams to involve real users before taking the next step. Remember, it is the user you're working for. Set up processes that allow feedback from actual 
users to reach the people responsible for making the product. 
82 These 10 principles demonstrate the breadth and depth of how wireframes can be used in the 
software process. Feel free to use them as a checklist for your project to verify that you've taken 
the right steps and involved the right people before you move on to code. 
83 Prototyping 
Prototyping is taking the initial concept, then iterating it through several cycles in between 
concept and production. There are three aspects of prototyping: build, review, then refine, and 
iterate, which leads to a rebuild until the design is ready for production. A prototype brings 
innovation to life users will see something emerge that they can interact with; they will see the 
ideas they proposed take form. These iterations can incorporate new thoughts and ideas that 
occur during the pro cess or even address bugs or issues that emerge. The Internet, for 
instance, was not initially designed for the type of security needed to take care of credit card 
transactions; however, later iterations have had to address these issues and needs. Prototy pes are UX Process Stage Deliverables that mock up final products.

Mid tohigh fidelity 
mockups often mimic a final product in further iterations, but a prototype is not a real product 
with all its functionality its purpose is to validate an application idea by letting real users 
experience it. UX designers use prototypes to evaluate usability and feasibility. From user 
testing to eventual, final implementation, UX designers spend hours redesigning and polishing 
an app, software, or product to meet the ne eds of end users. Figure 30. Digital Prototyping 
Information architecture is a science of organizing and structuring the content of websites, web 
and mobile applications, and social media software. IA aims at organizing content so that users 

84 would easil y adjust to the functionality of the product and could find everything they need 
without big effort. Imagine moving into a house and having the furniture just stuck in each room 
with no rhyme or reason the house is unlivable. Of course, once the items ar e in a room, they 
need organization and placement that makes using that room logical and comfortable. The 
same would be true, say, for a website design. One starts with categories and ideas, with 
desired pathways and functionality. But this needs to be lai d out and structured with the user 
experience in mind; IA aims at organizing the content needed for the clients information and 
processes. The structure should entice users into deep exploration, engage them with the 
content, and enable them to take neede d action. There is a question of the difference between Information Architecture and User Experience 
Design. Lets focus on specific aspects of IA: IA is a blueprint of the design structure that can be 
generated into wireframes, providing initial attempts at sitemaps of the project. UX designers 
then use these items as the basic materials to plan navigation systems. In that way, UX design 
entails much more than content structuring it aims at making pleasant interaction models so 
that users feel comfortab le using the product. The principles of IA science are a foundation of efficient design in that it forms a skeleton of any 
design project. Compelling and awesome UIs can fail without IA because it principally provides 
visual elements, functionality, int eraction, and navigation mapping. IA is one dimensional but is 
vital to how UX takes it to two dimensions. The thirddimension deals with inclusivity and 
accessibility for all users, then the fourth dimension is focused on innovation. 
85 Another design appr oach used to establish navigation is Card Sorting, which is especially useful 
for a large number of pages or products. The question is how to navigate beyond just a search 
function. Card sorting uncovers users mental models for better information architec ture. Card 
sorting is a UX research method in which study participants group individual labels written on 
notecards according to criteria that make sense to them. The task is challenging as it not only 
sorts and labels categories of information that need t o be accessible, it also addresses 
hierarchies of information within each category. Multiple participants are involved so that you 
can compare the thought processes between individuals to determine the most logical and 
reasonable structuring of information . This task can be done physically, such as being written 
out or with stickies, but it is very possible to do it virtually and remotely as well. Figure 31. Card Sorting: Uncover users mental models for better information architecture 
There are two types of card sorting exercises: open card sort and closed card sort. In the open 
method, participants sort topics from content on your website into categories that make sense to 
them, naming each group they create as it makes the most sense to them. This can prove 
valuable in the early stages of development, especially if you dont know yet how the content will 
be structured. It helps uncover whether different people within your target group have different 

86 assumptions when it comes to findin g the desired information it can determine where people 
would expect to reasonably find what they are looking for. Closed card sorting works with a predefined set of categories, so testers sort the content of a 
website or app into these established par ameters. This helps uncover whether or not users 
agree on the categories that have already been built, whether still in the planning stages or 
already established online.

It is useful in determining how distinct and appropriate the decided 
categories actua lly are, so if a lot of testers sort the same cards into completely different 
categories, designers are alerted that structural refinement may be necessary. A/B testing is a side byside comparison to determine preference. This can help with color 
scheme s, image and text placement, and overall design so that with each comparison and 
refinement, a better iteration is produced. There is a process for A/B testing, starting with the 
issue. Focusing on the issue helps isolate and determine the precise problem. Cause theory in 
concluding what is causing the problem or confusion so that it can be addressed and remedied. Variation hypothesis lays out proposed changes, which then sets goals, the outcomes that are 
expected from the implemented changes. Design syst ems are gaining popularity as helpful information in planning different design 
choices. Terminology for design systems includes style guides, pattern libraries, and component 
libraries. Style guides layout color palettes, font types and sizes, headings, an d other choices 
that bring coherence to design. Pattern libraries help with establishing patterns within a website, 
software, or app often tied to navigation. Text boxes, buttons, and returning to previous pages 
are examples of patterns that would regularl y be needed and found in pattern libraries. A 
chosen pattern should be consistently used across a platform, so a pattern library gathers tried 
and tested options for these choices. Component libraries collect functions such as drop down 
controls, toggles, sliders, menus, icons, payment methods, labeling schematics, checkboxes, 
etc. Users like consistency, so the design systems are key in establishing this throughout a 
platform. This is especially important when dealing with sub domain websites so users can have 
87 similar experiences within a system. In UX design, we are minimizing confusion for a better user 
experience, so design systems help bring reliability and consistency to design. What are the benefits of a design system? For one, there is a time saving s of being able to 
replicate pre designed functionality. One is not having to reinvent the wheel for each new 
component. Second, there is a better user experience across products familiarity in the 
function gives a more intuitive experience and, theref ore, less confusion for the user. Third, 
there is a higher consistency in design, code, and brand, thereby lessening cognitive and 
emotional friction. Last, there is increased team communication so that more stakeholders are 
on board and invested in the pr oduct. Even if there are a hundred iterations to ensure that there 
is approval across the board, it is worth it to produce a superior, highly polished product. Figure 32. Helpful information in planning different designs
