UX as it relates to products, systems, or platforms, must be carefully crafted, and not 
take anything for granted. Simply moving a button on a website can severely impact a 
companys reach. At one point the web browser Firefox moved its download button from the 
front center of a webpage to a lower position, requiring users to scroll down to see it; this 
resulted in the loss of millions of downloads per month. What is the deeper meaning of UX? Up until this point, we have been discussing UX in terms of the feelings, moments, and 
memories a product can create in a user. There are key aspects to consider that occur within 
UX. One would be friction resulting from issues within a user experience. There may be 
cognitive, emotio nal, and physical friction. A UX designers job is to reduce the friction in any of 
these areas as much as possible. Cognitive friction is when the user is overwhelmed by the amount of information that 
needs to be processed at any stage of an experience. I n many cases, less is more to avoid 
bombarding a user with data or instructions.

So, there is a huge amount of potential in making websites, software products, web 
applications, and native apps accessible. Based on the four principles of being perceivable, 
operable, understandable, and robust, there are thirteen guidelines, and each of the guidelines 
has six criteria for a total of seventy eight. It is useful to look at a few of these guidelines to shed light on their intent. Level A 1.1.1 deals 
with non text content so that all such content that is presented to the user has a text alternative 
that serves an equivalent purpose. That means there is a tex t alternative added to all images, all 

171 audio and video, and an added name to all controls, such as search and submit. This is the 
most basic level criteria, and, as you can see, these additions can help people that have audio 
or visual problems to see and hear key components of a web interface. For instance, if there 
is a picture of a beach, instead of the alt tag for the image saying image, text would be more 
descriptive such as, image is of sandy shoreline with surfers riding crashing waves. T hese 
kinds of additions would allow a blind person to engage more with the web content. Being accessibility conscious raises accessibility intelligence, a term coined for when a 
designer begins to look, see, and take into consideration the kinds of el ements and additions 
necessary to help engage the disabled. This requires empathy; when there is empathy, 
designers are at the forefront. Developers partner with designers to be forward thinking when 
making applications, websites, and products accessible. Understanding the depth and breadth 
of the thirteen guidelines and their seventy eight criteria is a process but it is a process that 
must have a beginning and then continually evolve. Any designer has all of this information at 
his or her fingertips. Th e larger a team of developers, of course, the greater the burden can be 
shared to ensure that a website, app, or program is 100% accessible. Level AA 1.3.4 deals with orientation, where content does not restrict its view and operation to a 
single display orientation, meaning it works portrait or landscape. Laptops are mostly in the 
landscape, while tablets and phones naturally orient as portraits. These guidelines allow for 
differing orientations whether one is on an online video site, messaging website, o r eReader 
web application. For some who are visually disabled, being able to go from portrait to landscape 
allows for bigger text and zoom capabilities. To give an idea of the depth and range of the criteria, lets look at the specificity of Level AAA 
2.5.5, which deals with target size. Specifically, the size of the target for pointer inputs is at least 
44 by 44 CSS pixels with a couple of exceptions. Regardless of the level, all criteria have the 
end goal of improving the quality of life for those with l ow, moderate, or severe disabilities. Level 
AAA 2.5.5 is to help those with motor skill issues or possible vision disabilities: If buttons are 
172 small and close together, a user might hit cancel instead of submit, causing a reset of the 
task he or she wa s trying to complete. Level AAA 2.5.5 ensures website buttons are big enough, 
so the wrong input is not selected. Granted, a large button is often mid ranged, a little large for 
the average user, but perhaps still not as big as what someone with a severe visual disability 
would prefer. To really do a deep dive, visit the following website: 
https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Understanding/ 
How does everything fit together? Developers employ developme nt authoring tools called IDEs 
(individual development environment) that have technical specifications embedded such as 
HTML, ARIA, CSS, etc., and accessibility guidelines (ATAG, WCAG, UAAG) as well. Developers can test whether they are meeting accessibil ity guidelines, and users can use 
assistive technologies and browsers to test to what extent guidelines have been met. It is 
meticulous work when attempting to implement accessibility. When we look at physical accessibility, it is usually the assumption th at users are not disabled. For instance, when a shopper requests directions to the checkout in a store, often a clerk will 
point and say, Over there.

If the shopper is visually impaired, this is of little help. It is the same 
in digital accessibility there is often the assumption that the user is not disabled. Therefore, 
accessibility in the design must be intentional. There are many areas to consider when designing for accessibility. One facet is designing for 
color blind individuals. To complicate th e task, there are different types of color blindness. Some 
color combinations are not appropriate for color blind people. There are color blindness 
reference charts that compare color interpretation for the different variations of the condition. Many compa ny logos utilize a normal gamut of colors, neglecting the reality of color blind 
individuals, which means their logo is not perceived in the same way by their entire audience. So, how are we mindful of design for those who are color blind? It is best to s tart with color 
contrast. Also, dont rely on color shapes and text should be used as well, whenever possible. Ensuring accessible controls is also useful, so employ UI (user interface) elements like links, 
173 buttons, checkboxes, etc. In addition, make the image readable with a descriptive alt text, and 
be sure to enable keyboard accessibility features. We have discussed violations in an earlier 
chapter, that some elements of design are meant to stand apart from others so when 
designing for the color blind, these violations are not just color but shape and placement as well. To ensure all these design choices are working in concert, perform accessibility tests. What about making email more disability friendly? It is possible to make outlook emails mo re 
accessible to blind and low vision individuals. One idea is to include alt text with any image. Just 
like this is possible for web pages, it is a simple function in email, as well. Alt text can be added 
to shapes, SmartArt graphics, and charts, too. Tex t reading features are also helpful, saving the 
visually impaired significant time by getting to listen to text rather than trying to follow highly 
magnified text. Designing for people with cognitive disabilities must take a lot of potential issues into 
consideration. As a designer, one must visualize what the user is seeing and encountering in 
the interface, then think with empathy about how to best introduce and layout components and 
interactions. As a designer, I ask how I can transform what must be unde rstood and 
manipulated by the user so that interactive opportunities are engaged, and learning can occur 
despite cognitive disabilities. Will the cognitively impaired user be able to utilize opportunities in 
the interface or capitalize on any learning pote ntial that is available? Autism is a specific case in point. There are suggested dos and donts when designing for 
users on the autism spectrum. Simple, soothing colors are preferable; avoid bright, contrasting 
colors. In terms of language, the more straightforward and exact the language, the better using 
figures of speech and idioms will confound understanding. When it comes to formatting, use 
simple sentences and bullets, and stay away from walls or large blocks of text. Build simple and 
consisten t layouts vs. complex and cluttered layouts. Buttons should be clear and descriptive, 
not vague, general, or unpredictable. For instance, click here does not mean much without a 
clear reason to do so. 
174 Designing for users with low vision also has some ke y dos and donts. Good color contrasts 
and large, readable font sizes will be effective while low color contrasts and small fonts sizes will 
be problematic. If possible, allowing a reader the ability to change the font size is a great 
feature. It is important to publish all necessary information on web pages. Burying information in 
downloads and links that might be overlooked or not seen should not happen. For colors, 
always combine colors, shapes, and text but do not use color only to convey meanin g. Lack of 
context and grounding will be confusing. Another consideration is to follow a logical and linear 
layout, where even 200% magnification is framed within a page content should not spread 
outside the screen framing. If an application does not hav e magnification capabilities, this can 
even cause problems with normal users if any content is small and needs to be zoomed in to be 
readable.

Also, related buttons and notifications should be located near each other to provide 
context separating actions from their related context is a challenge for normal users, so low 
vision users will more easily miss these connections. Proximity is paramount. Remember our discussion of designing with Gestalts Principles: Colors and contrast can 
certainly help divide or separate groups, but proximity overpowers other signals of distinction. Two columns of dots of one color separated from two other columns of dots of another color will 
seem like two distinct groups. But, if the colors are mixed between all the columns and they 
retain the same distance from each other, they will still seem like two separate groups even 
though the color distinction was lost. Designing for people who have auditory disabilities is another consideration. Of course, there is 
a great range be tween normal hearing and someone being completely deaf. Most issues will 
surround video and audio files, so content that is video only or audio only should be avoided. That doesnt mean there should be no audio or video files, but it does mean that transcr ipts or 
subtitles should be provided. We see closed captioning in most places such as YouTube, 
Amazon Prime, and most streaming services. Subtitles have the additional benefit of helping 
people who do not understand the language being spoken, whether it is a language foreign to 
175 us, the actors have a heavy accent, are speaking too quickly, or talking too quietly. The more 
features available to make content accessible, the better. Consider a hierarchical structure that groups text alongside relevant video or audio content. These separations make it visually clear that the user is seeing material that facilitates 
understanding of media with sound. Keeping long blocks of content with no differentiating 
material that explains audio and video limit the comprehens ion of those struggling with auditory 
disabilities. If there is an opportunity or ability to offer an interpreter or chat feature for booking 
appointments or asking questions, both are a far better option than making a phone call the only 
means of contact for users obviously, this would immediately be a hurdle or exclude those with 
hearing problems. Dyslexia is a common learning disability and those afflicted will obviously struggle with 
decoding text in an app or a website. What are the best practices to help the comprehension of 
these individuals? For one, using images and diagrams to support text is helpful. This is another 
disability where large blocks of heavy text can cause difficulties, which can slow down even 
normal users without disabilities. Consistency is also important text should be standardly 
aligned to the left with a regular layout (in appropriate countries), avoiding underlining, italics, 
and writing in all caps unless grammatically necessary. For those struggling with dyslexia, 
consi der producing materials in other formats, with perhaps audio or video complementing 
lengthy text. Also, if there are ideas or concepts from previous pages, give reminders and 
prompts rather than just expecting users to remember crucial information. This wi ll cause 
emotional friction from frustration or humiliation. As much as possible, systems we design 
should be assistive, making interaction and use as easy as possible.

This chapter will cover a variety of topics in User Experience and Acc essibility Design, including 
Interaction Design, PET (persuasion, emotion, & trust), Mobility, User Interface Designs, and 
Frameworks. IxD, or Interaction Design, entails all interactions a user experiences with a brand, product, or 
service. Specifically, IxD is the design of interactive products and services. A designers focus 
goes beyond the item in development to include the way users wi ll interact with it. Within its 
scope are visual representations, words, behavior, physical objects or space, and time. Visual representations might be something like a button a user can click to interact. Directly 
connected is behavior. So, if a user cl icks the visual representation of a button, there must then 
be a response or reaction this is behavior. Save buttons save; cancel buttons cancel the 
action. In other words, the corresponding behavior matches the visual representation. Of 
course, the visu al representations are usually accompanied by wording and direct wording is 
best so that the user understands the function of whatever is being labeled.

Wording such as 
save and cancel are obvious and common, but there are specialized and less common 
labels, such as Lets Get Started after introductory or explanatory text that would signal to the 
user, they are beginning a more in depth process or interaction. Sometimes representations of 
physical objects are used to identify functions: a pencil is regularly used in place of edit, and a 
trash can identifies erasing progress, information, or files. Naturally, any interaction with a system will take the users time. Cancel might be 
instantaneous, while save or edit might consume more time depe nding on factors such as 
size of file and complexity of the task. Any direction an application provides can make users feel 
more comfortable and confident that users can rely on the system. Just like free breadsticks 
being brought to a table while someone is waiting for their food to be prepared, apps like FedEx 
177 or Uber have indicators of wait time or the ability to track in real time the progress of a package 
or ride. This is an example of providing direction for a more satisfying user experience. Recallin g our iceberg discussion from an earlier chapter, User Interface is the tip of the iceberg. UI is what gives the user the opportunity to interact with the product. Users are only familiar with 
the experiences they go through, but those experiences give com panies data of the interaction, 
whether it is saved information, feedback, purchases, etc. Of course, all this springs from what 
the user needs or desires and what a particular business or service requires. User experience 
includes a service or business wh ich provides an opportunity to interact with its product within a 
user interface. User experience provides the means to bridge the gap between the consumer 
and the needed business. For a user experience designer to be thorough and successful, he or 
she mus t delve into the business itself to understand how to communicate and provide the value 
of the product to the consumer. Interaction design (IxD) is a subset of user experience. User Experience is the overall 
experience with the product while Interaction De sign examines how a user and product respond 
to each other. IxD doesnt simply determine the quality of interactions but whether the 
interactions are needed in the first place. If there is another, more efficient process or method 
than initially created, I xD can address these changes. Also, it is better to not have to create 
something from scratch if something existing can be enhanced, adapted, or expanded to 
accomplish the same purpose. In this way, IxD is not just creating interactions, it is also not 
creating interactions as well. In a way, a UX designer is a strategist for a company – any 
decision to create an interface entail extended time and resources from the company to 
maintain whatever is created; therefore, decisions to not create certain interacti ons, if 
unnecessary, will save a company time and money. There are five things to consider when designing an interaction: Is it learnable, consistent, 
predictable, perceivable, and does it provide feedback? For instance, if there is a button, you 
can pred ict that it will have a function. Buttons should be consistent, both in look and feel, and 
178 should have expected, perceivable results from their use. Any interaction must be perceivable 
for it to be accessible to the user. How learnable are these interactio ns so that any friction from 
user interaction is quickly reduced? If something is not working or is challenging to the user, the 
option to provide feedback is crucial to improve UX. In Mobile Interaction Design, the focus is on touch gestures. How would a user know to swipe 
left or right, or scroll up and down? There must be an indication that suggests a continuity 
pattern. Often the solution is highlighted – the focus is on bright col ors with lowlight or muted 
colors for further options at the edges. When a user sees partial information in subdued hues at 
the edge of the interface, it naturally suggests that another interaction is available. To clearly distinguish between User Experie nce design and User Interface design, there are 
clear boundaries and definitions to quickly differentiate the two. User Experience pertains to 
interaction design, wireframes and prototypes, information architecture, user research, and 
scenarios.

User Inter face entails visual design, color choices, graphic design, layout, and 
typography. Progressive disclosure is an important concept to understand in User Experience. The idea is to 
not give out information until the user needs it. This is one of the reasons for menus. Users do 
not need to see all the links in a website all the time; in this case, the information is available via 
something like a dropdown menu if the user desires to view it, but it is otherwise hidden. These 
kinds of options prevent the user interface from being cluttered, confused, or overwhelming. Progressive disclosure is a strategy for managing information complexity. When it is used, only 
the information necessary at that point in the interaction is shown. It is a simple yet powerful 
design pattern that only displays the more advanced functionalities of the app interface as the 
user interacts with it. For instance, a task like changing a password is seldom necessary, so it 
would be hidden in a submenu until there is a need. The last secti on of this chapter will touch on some trends in Mobile User Interface and User 
Experience. The dominating landscape of this area is portrait mode, designing around how the 
179 user holds most mobile devices. Simplicity and use of white space is at the forefron t. Since most 
of the interaction is with the thumb, the standard is one swipe, one touch, one click. The focus is 
on design being suggestive and intuitive to minimize confusion and reduce cognitive friction.

This chapter will be diving into the industry concept of PET (persuasion, emotion, and trust), and 
I will be extending that to EET (empathy, emotion, and trust). Both seek to do the right thing by 
users. When we employ these techniques for user experience and user interface design, we 
build a foundation of connection with the user. The idea behind this is fair exchange: one side is 
trying to sell a service or a product through a persuasive user experience that promotes a 
positive emotional response, perhaps even establishing a need in the user. Through this 
process, trust is built. Not only does this help sales, but the user also becomes a salesperson 
via word of mouth. The user becomes a part of the salesforce – if my friend persuades me to buy 
an iPhone due his or her PET or EET with the p roduct, all the better for the company. Building trust with loyal users automatically develops an emotional attachment. When trust and 
emotional attachment is there, they will subsequently persuade other people. Trust in 
relationships will often override resistance in individuals in a way that direct contact with a 
company may be unable to do. It is often a process over time that can be understood with 
Codes hierarchy of persuasion.

The first level is usabili ty, where the user can say, I can do X, which is removing physical 
barriers in the way of performance. Next, trust is developed, where the user sees, It is OK to do 
X UX builds the basics for their engagement. Third, an emotional engagement is bu ilt up – 
users are engaged the right way to encourage action, where they want to do X. Last is a 
persuasion trigger, nudging them to take action, where they say, I will do X. People often can

comprehend, and interact. It gives a high level view of information and can build familiarity and

and invest in the product. They have converted into an actual consumer, and the hope is they 
will return with fu rther business.

appraising the level of emotion they have for anything they need or want. One can then parlay

different makes and models may also be useful to help decide for some individuals. For others,

faces – there is a lot of pers onal connection through what is communicated in peoples 
expressions. Telling a story is also very powerful when users can relate to it. Of course, theres 
183 no guarantee for buy in, but any of these factors can translate into a commitment from the

or lose the deal with professionalism if it is not whats best for the consumer. This approach

operated from a PET perspective. After a two hour dialogue, when he felt we were not ready to

on when he could have made the sale, took his comm ission, and exited the picture. His 
empathy with us forged a life long relationship where I often throw business his way because I 
was so impressed with his abilities and character. The take away is that we can build long term

effort of the listener – in this case the UX de signer – and the greater understanding and 
engagement that results. The lowest level is pity, which communicates, I am sorry for you. Next is sympathy, where one feels for another, whereas empathy communicates, I feel with 
you.

The highest level is comp assion, where one is emotionally moved by another. Consider 
184 designing a website for a non profit organization – here, we can see the need to move the user

An empathy map can help us understand how a user is processing information. There are four

user thinks, which may be less guarded as the user is asked to think out loud while going

observing what works easily, what is intuitive, and what is a challenge. The last quadrant is to 
see what the user is pleased with or what is causing frustration. This can be done through 
observation and non verbal cues or by asking questions based on observation. Each quadrant

design. One way to use an empathy map. What is empathy? Before we understand what, an empathy map is, lets unpack just what empathy is. Tim Brown,

Its not us versus them or even us on behalf of them. For a design 
thinker it must be us with them

rid them of it. Like a doctor, only for technological illnesses. Why is this important? Because

products and services. And when we can do that, it can lead to a more successful user 
experience. Empathy should be your g oal.

map is. Is it a way to guide us to being more empathetic when thinking of our users? Kind of. But its more than that. An empathy map is a UX design asset that helps designers and non designers understand and 
visualize a users needs. It slots into your workflow before you get involved in interactive 
prototyping. The empathy map allows UX designers to map their target audience in the best way possible. Not to be confused with a user persona, an empathy map works alongside user personas. Be sure to create a user persona before you get involved in making your empathy map. How do you m ake an empathy map? First, you need to grab your colleagues and some stakeholders. A set of decent pens and a 
whiteboard. An empathy map should only take about an hour of your time because youre 
building on a pre defined user persona. An empathy map is usually broken down into four quadrants and populated with sticky notes. The four quadrants are thinking and feeling, seeing, hearing and doing. What they think and feel. Here is where you think consider the users aspirations, the ir hopes and their dreams. Do 
they have any ambitions? What makes them feel good? Or bad? 
187     What they hear. What are their friends telling them? Their boss? Maybe their family. And, in the age of 
social media, what are influencers are saying. What they see. Whats in their environment? What is the market offering them? What they say and do. Their appearance, their behavior, their attitudes. Aside from these four quadrants, you can also add two sections on pains and gains.

These 
sections will outline the difficulties and obstacles your user experiences as well as what they 
hope to achieve. A pain, for example, may be that a user struggles to navigate a website and in their frustration, 
closes it and blames themselves. A goal migh t look like something such as buy a ticket for a 
movie in 5 minutes or less. Empathy Map s aids in the design process . These can also be composed of both qualitative and 
quantitative data and can also be used in conjunction with your user persona after it i s created, 
making it a by product of the persona. 
188 
Figure: Empathy Map  by Pedro Sanoja [Ref: 4] 
Empathy Maps revolve around the target user and are usually broken down into four sections: 
what they think, feel, say, and do. What does an empathy map look like? Lets imagine youre in the process of designing a new ticketing system for music events. Remember, you dont need to spend an eternity on an empathy map, nor does it have to be a 
work of art – just 30 minutes to an hour. You might take one of y our pre defined user personas 
and then create an empathy map that looks something like this: 

189 
From this, you will have a better idea for designing solutions to Janes problems – because 
youve got into her head, understood her needs and wants. When you have a complete 
empathy map, its a good idea to glean insights from your notes. These insights should be noted 
out of the map, on a separate piece of paper or document. The insights should ideally be 
focused on a users needs, in lieu of their desires. Benefits of empathy maps in UX design 
The reason we use empathy maps is because they allow designers to see and understand the 
worldview of their users. Other benefits include: 
Quick and cheap to create 

190 Fit into your prototyping workflow 
Can be iterated upo n with real data 
Identify key insights 
Understand target personas better 
Whether its creating a new website or product, if you dont design with empathy, theres a risk 
that your product will not meet your users needs, and this will result in a product t hat fails. Sure, an empathy map wont be the key to total business success but when youre able to 
assuage any problems or frustrations in your user, youre on step closer to that success 
regardless. Its one less hurdle. Empathy maps are a cheap way to kn ow your audience in a more intimate way and a method to 
practice robust design thinking. Empathy is the cornerstone of great design because design 
does best when it solves problems and when youre empathetic, you know exactly what your 
user is feeling. And when you can empathize, you design better. Empathy map is to generate sticky notes for questions, observations, thoughts, and reactions 
for each quadrant, as appropriate. Then, as a UX designer, as each of the sticky notes is 
addressed through review and reiteration of design, the sticky can then be removed to show 
progress. Empathy mapping is a great tool to evaluate whether your design is meeting your 
goals with users. 
191 
Figure 43. Empathy Map 
 
What does empathy mapping accomplish? For one, it removes bias from our designs and aligns 
a design team, development team, or even an entire company on a single, shared 
understanding of the user. Also, it discovers weaknesses in user or market research – it helps 
uncover potentially unknown or undiscovered factors about target customers and products. Third, it may uncover user needs that user themselves may not even be aware existed. If 
significant, it becomes easy to highlight this need as a product featu re. Uncovering a gap in the 
marketplace allows a UX designer to make the product more attractive to consumers. We also 
can come to understand what drives users behavior that can then guide us towards meaningful 
innovation. This information makes it easier to be responsive to user needs in our UX design. 
192 There are three levels of emotional design to consider. One is time, another is heart toheart 
connection, and the third is perception of what is being presented. The goal in emotional design 
is to create enduring, delightful, and engaging product experiences.

Theres tremendous depth 
here in just a few words. How do we discover where delight occurs? When we understand 
behavioral patterns of users, their visceral responses and thinking processes, and how th ey 
reflect on their own thinking, we can sometimes anticipate what exactly in our designs could 
elicit a delighted response. Of course, these are challenging aspects to pin down as they occur 
within a users mind, so it may take a lot of trial and error to achieve. A UX designer is 
empathetically stepping into users minds to better target their needs and expectations. There are five secrets to discuss for Interactive Design. One is that humans come first – are we 
connecting? This entails many of the aspec ts this chapter has been discussing. Second is 
designing for comfort and predictability, especially for mobile devices. If there is a certain area 
of a screen the thumb can reach, the thumb zone, then a good deal of functionality should be 
put in reach o f this area. Quick and primary functions are always put within reach of the thumb. Third is to connect emotionally, and the value of this aspect has been established with our 
discussion of PET and EET. Fourth, we want to design with mental triggers. For in stance, this 
entails using common, recognizable forms, like hamburger menus, that gives users a drop 
down menu when activated. Regular users now recognize this design and understand its 
function. Buttons and volume control are other examples of mental tr iggers. We should leverage 
common devices rather than innovating something new whenever possible in order to save time 
and money. Last is to design with simplicity. Leonardo di Vinci said, Simplicity is the ultimate 
sophistication there is something a ppealing and beautiful in the simple. It is useful to know levels of UI design and development. The most basic framework is HTML, 
the backbone or skeletal system. Javascript and CSS (cascading style sheets) are common UI 
features for website design. Ther e are also the highest level of features for advanced UI design, 
like dropdowns and reactive functions. There are crucial UI design frameworks of which to be 
193 aware. These include Material Design from Google, Flat Design, Apple Design Frameworks, 
Angular U I Framework from Google, ReactJs Framework from Facebook, and Bootstrap 
Framework from Twitter. All are free open source libraries that are valuable to research and 
develop a foundational understanding of their functionality. An innovation I have been developing is the PXI Framework, which is a Product eXperience 
Index. It is a way to measure the quality of a users experience with any given product based on 
ten factors. A score is given out of ten for each of the following ca tegories: usability, user 
experience, desirability, security/privacy, performance/reliability, accessibility, being value 
oriented, scalability, maintainability, and extensibility. The sum total of these scores out of 100 
gives the PXI. It is a useful tool to measure the success of ones UX. Responsive web design 
should be a given now, so a goal would be a 90 or higher for ones PXI. Culturally, we have 
moved from multi channel organization to omni channel innovation. Multi channel meant that 
different aven ues such as stores, the web, mobile devices, social apps, and phone were not all 
integrated; omni channel means all of these components are now connected. Increased 
convenience and connectedness for the user can mean more challenges and obstacles for UX 
design– so tools such as the PXI framework can be quite useful to measure success.

206 Chapter 10: Designing the Low Fidelity Wireframes  
 
This chapter is designed to guide you through creating your first wireframe levering a 
great tool Balasmiq wireframes . The website where you can find the tool is 
https://balsamiq.com/ . We will cover a basic overview of the product as well as some 
of the features and UI controls . Here is the wireframe that you will create in this 
exercise . A product page on website that has product images slider, product name and 
details and finally products overview, features, design and sp ecs 
 
Always try and start and UX design project with low fidelity wireframes. This way the 
potential users and stakeholders are not caught up in the visual design, icons, colors, 

207 fonts etc. The goal is focus on the user experience, user flow and optimizi ng the 
experiences so that the users can accomplish the tasks efficiently and effectively. Basic concepts and terminology 
Here are some of the basic components of Balsamiq Wireframes: 
UI Control  A standard user interface "widget" (e.g., Button, Image, Dialog Window). The building blocks of any wireframe. Canvas  The grid lined area where UI Controls are placed. UI Library  A row of UI Controls that can be dragged onto the Canvas. Property Inspector  A configuration panel that contains common actions (e.g. alignment, layering) and properties that are specific to each UI Control. Property Inspector 
The Property Inspector allows you to set some common properties for controls, such as 
alignment, position, and size as well as specific settings for certain controls (selection state, text 
properties, color, etc.). It is available when viewing wireframes, assets, and Symbols. You can 
show and hide the Proper ty Inspector by clicking the toggle icon above it (keyboard 
shortcut CTRL /⌘+; or ALT/OPTION +ENTER ). When hidden you can also show it by right 
clicking a control and selecting "Properties...". If you have multiple controls selected it will show properties that are common to all selected 
controls as well as options for aligning and distributing. When no controls are selected the 
Property Inspector shows notes for the selected wireframes, asset, or Symbol. In the wireframes 
view the panel also show s wireframe alternates . Research the show alternates feature in 
balsamiq. For assets and Symbols, it also shows the count and name of wireframes where the 
selected object is used.

208 
Figure: Property Inspector 
Please refer to entire documentation of the balsamiq the tool which we have been referencing 
https://balsamiq.com/wireframes/cloud/docs/overview/ for an extensive learning of this low 
fidelity tool. Below figure show the balsamiq navigation, UI library, ca nvas and property panel 

209

242 Introduction to UI Design Patterns 
A design pattern is a reusable solution to a commonly occurring problem. As a recipe in 
cooking provides the ingredients and structure that make up a recognizable dish, so too doe s a 
design pattern provide an identifiable and predictable solution to an interface design problem. The idea of design patterns initially came from architecture and programming, where the idea 
was to optimize solutions that are known to work well within gi ven contexts. 1 Solutions that 
emerged frequently enough became recognized as a formula that can be reused . Structural and behavioral features of a pattern are familiar to users.

Your team can leverage this 
knowledge, rather than reinventing the wheel, to provide greater ease and use of their product. It is good to point out, however, that while design patterns are useful for informing design 
decisions around your problem, you may likely need to modify them around your users' and 
business' needs. We're going to start by looking at a design pattern, look at a few examples of the pattern in use, 
and deconstruct the ir implementation. Then we will list some common patterns for interface 
design, and you may explore them in depth. The Cooking Analogy: 
In cooking we combine ingredients to prepare a dish. Let's say for instance, we're planning to 
make a fish taco meal . If you're familiar with this dish, you know that you'll usually prepare it with 
a flaky fish like Cod perhaps, tortillas, different seasonings, oil, salsa, and maybe sliced lime for 
garnish. There are different ways to add to this dish to make it yours, but the basic combination 
of ingredients make a fish taco unmistakable . This is very much like using design patterns. We have a general model for how to create this 
243 dish to make it recognizable. We can add or subtract from those ingredients and how they're pu t 
together to make it unique. Elements of a design pattern 
Design patterns are typically written with a common set of attributes that looks something like 
this: 
Design pattern model 
Pattern Name (and description) 
o A label that provides a clear way to communicate and reference this pattern, 
particularly when discussing it with colleagues. Problem 
o Describe what problem this solves and why this pattern exists. Context 
o Describe when to use this solution. Solution 
o How it works. o Describe the solution in deta il. Recommendations 
o Provide further recommendations. Examples 
o Any applications leveraging the design pattern. 
244 Design pattern model 
Let's explore writing a design pattern for a website Shopping Cart component into this model. This seems like an obvious description of a very familiar component. While you're reading, think about how this compares to other purchasing experiences like a 
oneclick purchase, or how it compares to a similar purchase of a service like a reservation or 
booking experience. Think about how this might be different on a mobile phone for example. Pattern Name: Shopping Cart for E commerce Site 
 
Description: The Shopping Cart component consists of 1) An "Add to Cart" button to purchase 
an item and 2) an accompanying cart icon us ed to indicate that the item is held for purchase 
and provides a link to view the items and begin checkout. Problem: Users want to purchase an item in an e commerce site. Context of Use: Use this pattern when an online store allows browsing items, has mo re than a 
single item to purchase, or requires review of order before completing purchase. While shopping on an online store the user may select items to purchase, but want to continue 
browsing, and may want to review and edit what they've selected before beginning checkout. This is like holding items in a shopping cart in the physical world. Solution: 
1. Viewing Product and Adding an Item to Cart 
1. Present a button with the product to add the item to a shopping cart. 
245 
 
2. Updating and Previewing Cart 
1. When the user has selected the Add to Cart action, provide feedback that the 
item has been added. Show the item count increase in a numeric indicator next 
to the cart icon. 
2. Optionally show a preview of the cart with the item and the selected options 
displayed. 
3. Provide feedback about the next steps, for example editing the cart, viewing the 
full cart, continuing shopping, or beginning checkout to complete the purchase. 
3. Displaying the Shopping Cart 
1. Provide a separate Shopping Cart View of the items added to cart s o that the 
user may modify or complete their order. 
2. Provide actions for editing quantities, removing items. 
3. Provide an action for "checking out" or completing their purchase. Recommendations: 
Add to Cart may be presented with options, for example a selecto r for quantity, selectors 
for style, etc.

Provide conditional logic if the item requires options to be selected, for 
disable the Add to Cart button if style or size has not been selected. 
246 Consider a one click option for signed in users or navigate directly to the checkout 
process if the store offers a single item for purchase. Examples 
Nike 
Shopify 
Crate and Barrel 
 
Examples 
Let's look at 2 of the Shopping Cart examples listed above and go a little further to deconstruct 
how they solved this specific need and how this reflects the pattern. We will look at the point where a customer decides to purchase a product using the Shopping 
Cart metaphor in 2 sites: the Nike Store and Tatt.ly , a site that uses Shopify. Nike.com cart 
 

247 Tattly cart, which uses Shopify for e commerce
 
Comparison : In both examples, the design pattern is based on using the shopping cart as a 
metaphor for temporarily holding things you are going to purchase. There's a common 
iconography that's been established, th ere's usually an indicator of the number of items being 
held, and an assumption that the next step is to "check out" as one would do in the physical 
world at a store.

248 There are only subtle variations between these experiences. 
1. Nike provides a nice behavior to preview the cart without leaving the product page, 
perhaps making it easier for the user to return to shopping. In another site with a similar 
dialog to Nike's Crate and Barrel uses this same idea of previewing the Cart, but 
additionally promot es other products the customer might want to purchase based on 
what's in their cart. Nike promotes other products on the cart view itself. 
2. Shopify directs the user to the Cart immediately after adding a product to cart. In both Nike and Tatt.ly (Shopify), there's the same general behavior and structure of the 
experience. Instead of re creating the experience, for the most part, both sites rely on 
predictable conventions, which make up the common shopping cart pattern. Using and creating your own patterns 
It is likely that many of the interfaces you see were probably designed with a common design 
pattern in mind. The Cart example is one that is copied often because it is based on an 
understanding leveraging the recognizability of this pattern. It puts users a t ease, because they 
have expectations for how online shopping works, and it satisfies business needs to make the 
experience as frictionless as possible, while also looking for valuable add on sale opportunities. As you begin to use design patterns, remember that while they are great for helping you 
inform your design decisions when solving a common UI problem, they're not meant to be 
copied without thinking about your users' and product's particular needs. Jennifer Tidwell, who 
wrote an exc ellent interface design book titled Designing Interfaces, gave this word of advice 
about using patterns in the section called "About Patterns." "They aren't offtheshelf 
components; each implementation of a pattern is a little different from every other. They aren't 
249 simple rules or heuristics either. And they won't walk you through an entire set of design 
decisions..."

Lean (Startup) UX 
Lean startup UX is all about measuring and Validating Product/Market Fit. We have this great 
Agile machine allowing us to be crazy efficient in shipping software. But, um, did anyone check 
to see if we are shipping the right software ? A Lean UX approach shows us that shipping, which 

254 is the big honking Done in the Agile world, is in fact really only the beginning. While Agile 
methods help UX designers turn old ways of designing and communicating on their head, Lean 
UX helps us overturn old approaches to research and measuring quality . In a traditional model, research is something you do before starting to create the product, to 
figure out what the product is that you are going to build. In a Lean approach, we are 
continuously building and gathering metrics about what we have built. The most archetypal 
example of this is the metrics gathering landing page, which is created and launched at the very 
outset of the project, rather than soon before the finished product is about to be released. We 
turn what was once just seen as marketi ng fluff into an actual experiment of our hypothesis that 
others will think our idea is as great as we think it is. Then, the metrics gathered from that 
landing page (or it can evolve into a full fledged metrics gathering website) are fed back into the 
product design. But a landing page is just one of any number of ways one can apply Lean UX. Another common 
pattern is to create a simple prototype and GOOB! or Get Out of the Building! Many UX 
designers give lip service to the idea of User Centered Desig n, but do not actually spend a lot of 
facetime with real users . Regardless of if they do, GOOBing both rebrands and reshapes the 
idea of UCD and gives UX designers a nice kick in the butt to get out of their cozy cubicles and 
offices and take their ideas t o where the users are. We are, in this model, not doing research before or after the product is made but throughout the 
product design and delivery process . While in an Agile UX model, Building is Designing is 
Building, in a Lean UX model, Building is Rese arch is Building, and it is easy to see how these 
two are very much intertwined. Like with Agile UX, it allows for much more easily integrating 
research with how Agile teams work, since it is continuous and not up front. 
255 One more thing about Lean UX: it is kind of confusing . The term Lean has its origins in Lean 
Manufacturing and refers to the practice of minimizing waste and maximizing flow, which, in 
turn, is a cornerstone of Agile methods.

Lean St artup a la Eric Ries (and Steve Blank, basically the godfather of Lean Startup, and 
creator of concepts like Customer Development and Getting Out of the Building), which extends 
Agile ideas to include methods for ensuring that there in fact is a market for the product you are 
doing such a good job designing and shipping early and often. Bottom line: in everyday conversation, whether one uses the term Lean or Agile or what not is

Agile UX is all about collaboration and delivery. Agile was created by enterprise developers and 
looks at the software product from a developer perspective, similarly to how someone working in 
a restaurant kitchen looks at the restaurant at large. It is not that the stuff going on in the front of 
the house, the experience part of the restaurant, is n ot seen as important, it just is not the 
primary focus . Furthermore, in the enterprise world of old, which was a primary focus of Agile, 
software products were more akin to an institutional cafeteria anyway, i.e., highly utilitarian 
systems where the focus is on delivering the required features rather than a great user 
experience . As Ward Cunningham, one of the original signatories of the Agile Manifesto, once 
said at an Agile UX retreat at Cooper, Agile is hot food served quickly. 
256 Ultimately, Agile is ab out high quality high velocity delivery of working software . In the Agile 
universe, which is the ultimate measure of progress. However, a funny thing happened on the 
way to that Agile Manifesto. Making great software quickly, it turns out, requires collabo rating 
effectively with annoying non binary entities called people . While silent about UX design, Agile 
thinking offers a fundamental change in thinking about how to interact and communicate with 
the people on your team and beyond. So, while there certain ly is a lot that UX designers can learn from Agile thinking on software 
delivery (such as to automate everything that can be automated), the real pay off for UX 
practitioners is in the collaboration part. Agile UX methods, like Design Studio and Cross 
Func tional Pairing, help UX practitioners replace slow documents with fast and effective direct 
interaction. An Agile UX practice, in other words, replaces document centered practice with one 
that is collaboration centered . This is an excessively big deal for UX designers working on Agile 
teams, because it is this shift that is key in allowing them to integrate their practice with Agile 
Developers. Lean UX vs Agile UX

comparison between assorted designs , including the clients, could go a long way in shattering 
the myths they are embracing. Myths 
28 Myth 1 is that the fewer steps or clicks in a program, the better. This is not necessarily the case. If the UX designer has taken care of cognitive friction, physical friction, emotional fricti on, and 
what I call introductory friction, then the number of clicks does not matter. People do not care. Think about how many times you have counted the number of clicks in a product or service you 
have used online or in your company. Hardly at all! It is the stakeholders, not the users, which 
are counting the clicks. Of course, if any friction is high, then counting the clicks would make 
sense. However, we cannot get caught up in a general rule that something should only take 
three or four clicks. Figure 6. Myth 1: Lesser clicks 
All pages should be accessible in 3 clicks 
The three click rule or three click rule is an unofficial web design rule concerning the design 
of website navigation. It suggests that a user of a website should be able to find any information 
with no more than three mouse clicks. It is based on the belief that users of a site will become 
frustrated and often leave if they cannot find the information within the three clicks. Although there is little analytical evidence that this is the case, it is a commonly held belief 
amongst designers that the rule is part of a good system of navigation. Critics of the rule 

29 suggest that the number of clicks is not as important as the success of the clicks or information 
sent. Jeffrey Zeldman wrote, in Taking Your Talent to the Web (2001), that the Three Click Rule is 
"based on the way people use the Web" and "the rule can help you create sites with intuitive, 
logical hierarchical structures" 
The three click rule has been challenged by usability test results, which have shown that the 
number of clicks needed to access the desired information affects neither user satisfaction, nor 
success rate. In eCommerce websites, the rule can often be detrimental as to adhere to the 
rule, products on offer to customers must be grouped into categories that are far too large to be 
easily browsed. The Two Tap Rule — Merissa Mayer has something called the two tap rule of app design. The test for the rule, Mayer says, is simple: Once youre in the app, is it two taps to do 
anything you want to do? If no, time to redesign the app. The Yahoo Flickr app uses this to 
great effect: from the opening screen, you can take a picture, surf your screen, navigate 
albums, check out groups, set alerts, and more, all wi th just a couple taps. Usability tests have long challenged the so called three click rule or two tap rule . Contrary to 
popular belief, people dont leave your site or app if theyre unable to find the desired 
information in 3 clicks or taps. In fact, the number of necessary clicks affects neither user 
satisfaction, nor success rate. Thats right; fewer clicks dont make users happier and arent 
necessarily perceived as faster. What really counts here is ease of navigation, the 
constant scent of informa tion (you will find more information in the later chapter in this book the 
chapter name Advanced Concepts of UX Design about Information scent under Information 
forging ) along the users path. If you dont make the user, think about the clicks, they wont mind 
having a few extra clicks. 
30 
Myth 2 is to fill up the white space. White space has a place. Not every area needs to be busy 
or filled with an image or function. White space can declutter, separate elements, help people 
focus on what you really want the m to see, and even give people visual rest. Figure 7. Myth 2: Fill up white spaces 
 

31 Myth 3 is that scrolling is evil, that everything must fit in a browser frame. When you have to 
see 100 things on the same page and go from top to bottom, then scrolling is unwieldy and 
problematic. But again, when friction is reduced and scrolling is ju stified, then it is completely 
acceptable.

Traditional UX – it is not like it suddenly vanished

could be fu rther from the truth. As experience quality becomes an ever more critical factor in

hawing about for eons (ahem) about usability and superior design principles is as important as 
ever. Superior design is superior design , regardless of if we are living in an Agile or Lean or

Serial Positioning Effect 

259 You may not be aware of this, but it is likely that you have come across the serial position effect 
on more than one occasion. A concept coined by renowned psychologist, Hermann 
Ebbinghaus, the serial position effect refers to how the location of an item i n a sequence 
influences a persons memory or recall. The concept dictates that people usually remember items at the beginning or the end of a list or 
sequence with greater accuracy than those in the middle. User experience (UX) designers 
leverage the serial position effect to improve their designs and create a richer, more seamless 
experience for consumers. This approach to digital design is present in the websites, apps or 
landing pages of iconic brands such as Apple, Nike, or Electronic Arts (EA). Here we are going to explore the serial position effect in more detail, explore some notable 
design examples, and consider how you can use this powerful principle to improve your brands 
UX offerings. In this artic le we will go over: 
What is the serial position effect? Applying the serial position effect to design 
Serial position effect for landing page UX 
How to use experimentation in design 
What is the serial position effect? When it comes to UX optimization, the order of things matters . As humans, we do indeed tend 
to remember the items near the start or end of a list — much like our brains respond well to 
storytelling . 
260 
Figure: Serial Position Effect Visual representation. Hermann Ebbinghaus coined the phrase based on in depth studies on the short as well as long 
term memory and its impact on how we remember or perceive information. Th ese studies were 
further developed by psychologists B.Murdock in 1962 and Glanzer & Cunitz in 1966. These extensive studies resulted in the two vital serial position effect c oncepts: the primacy 
effect and the recency effect. Primacy effect 
The primacy effect is based on the discovery that an individual is likely to recall items, assets or 
information from the start of a list. For instance, when someone attempts to remember something from a long list of words, they 
are likely to recall the terms words listed at the beginning, rather the middle. 
261 As such, the primacy effect helps a user to remember the information they absorb 
first better than the information they see later in their journey (further down a landing page, for 
example). Recency effect 
The recency effect is a concept contrary to the primary effect. Rather than recalling information 
absorbed earlier on, the recency effec t is based on the notion of people remembering the 
information they see last with more clarity. This model is dependent on short term memory. A mix of studies suggests that the recency effect is prevalent in the courtroom . In many cases, 
jurors are more likely to recall, and agree with, the argument or conclusion they hear last. In a UX design context, for i nstance, a potential customer will recall the last two items they saw 
on a personalized product recommendation carousel and purchase one of these products as a 
result. The primacy and recency effect combined make up key elements of the serial position effe ct, 
which brings us onto our next point.

Applying the serial position effect to design 
 
Now that you understand the fundamental concepts of the serial position effect, were going to 
consider how you can apply it to design — or more specifically, to user design interfaces. Both the primacy and recency effect can have a significant impact on the design of user 
interfaces. Extensive lists of information put a strain on the human memory, often hindering 
perception and recall; and, by utilizing both ends of th e serial position effect spectrum (primacy 
and recency), you can enhance your designs significantly. 
262 By understanding that items or assets in the middle of a sequence are usually absorbed the 
least, it is possible to leverage the serial position effect to minimize the loss of 
information. In doing so, it is possible to create interface designs that are richer, more valuable, 
and easier to navigate. Considering that 38% of consumers will bounce off a web page if its layout is poor or 
unattractive, getting your design right will prove critical to your long term success. Applying the serial position effect to your interface design process is at its core, down to 
ensuring that users can navigate the items or information on your page intuitively. If your design is digestible, fluid, and seamless, users will recall vital information with more 
clarity while taking desired actions like signing up to a newsletter or buying a specific product. Here are four essential principles of applying the serial position effect to interface design: 
 1. Provide practical, task releva nt information  
Adding and maintaining task relevant information to your interface will not only make your 
design more engaging, but it will reduce the strain on users focus or recall. 
263 Figure: Medium User Interface ( Source ) 
 
Publishing platform Medium, for instance, has designed its user interface to simplify its 
interactions from a readers as well as a writers perspective. With a host of visual tools tailored to the us ers preferred topics or interests, you gain a visual 
snapshot of information that offers access to relevant content and to your reading list and allows 
you to create a new piece of content with swift, seamless actions.  2. Add recognizable cues 
Adding dyn amic cues to your user interface design minimizes cognitive strain while facilitating 
informational recall. Audible notifications ( e.g., pings when you receive a message) or textual cues (e.g. small 
informational pop up boxes) create a real sense of recog nition. Video games like Need for 
Speed or Broken Sword are excellent examples of cue based design for user interfaces. 
264 
Figure: Plants vs Zombies EA video game ( Source ) 
 EA Games once popular Plants vs Zombies game, for instance, utilizes a multitude of 
recognizable visual and audio cues to help players navigate their way through the game and 
remain in the moment without pushing them to their cognitive limits. Foleystyle sounds unique to each move the player makes (planting sounds, digging sounds 
etc.), text based captions that tell the player what to expect next, and visual icons at the top of 
the screen all work cohesively to make the user experience feel as nat ural as possible. You can 
apply similar cues to e commerce sites to enrich your designs and make them more intuitive.  3. Reduce the level of recall required 
The human attention span has its limits and, typically, can only retain five pieces of informatio n 
at any one time. If you prioritize limiting the necessity for recall, you will guide users through 
their journey in a way that helps them remember relevant information as and when required.

Applying effective design and copywriting principles to your various digital touchpoints while 
leveraging the serial position effect to deliver valuable information to your consumers will 
accelerate your commercial success. But, in an increasingly saturated digital age where the 
consumer has a wealth of their fingertips, how do you know if your design and serial position

bias can impact landing page browsing behavior. So, the best way to understand if your 
initiatives are working and experiment with design effective ly is though A/B testing. With 
a combination of effective data and the right A/B testing platform, it is possible to pinpoint a 
specific landing page or user interfaces strengths or weaknesses. By developing two versions of the same landing page, you can drill down into specific page 
elements and discover which performs best. 
273 For example, you might find that version A of a landing page is earning more engagement 
above the fold due to the design or placement of a Shop Now button. Through testing, you 
might also find that version B is converting more email subscribers because of a particular 
piece of copy or messaging. If you home in on this wealth of comparative information, you will gain the power to 
experiment with every design element imaginable, taking the best performing elements to 
create a fully optimized version of a specific page or touchpoint. A/B testing will give your design 
experimentation activities shape while protecting your marketing budget. If you understand which messaging or design e lements to focus on, you can get to the root of 
the issue and make tweaks for optimizations that are likely to offer the best possible return on 
investment (ROI).

Concerning the serial position effect, through A/B testing and experimentation 
you will be ab le to flatten the serial position curve to balance the information on your interfaces 
or landing pages. By balancing the information elements on your interfaces or landing pages, you can make your 
UX designs easier to navigate while improving brand engage ment. You will also gain the ability 
to experiment with design elements to emphasize the information or assets featured at the top 
or bottom of your digital touchpoints. If users arent engaging with the information at the top or bottom of a specific page, it will 
become clear that your serial position effect centric efforts arent working. From there, you 
can experiment with the hierarchy of your information in addition to design elements 
including buttons, color combinations, imagery, copy formatting, and text boxes.

We have outlined the fundamentals of the serial position effect and looked at how to apply the 
concept to UX and landing page design while outlining the importance of experimentation and 
testing. Reflecting on our journey, what is clear is that, in order to deliv er the very best designs 
and UX offerings to your consumers, you need to reduce cognitive strain as much as possible. The serial position effect helps us to understand human limitations in terms of both long 
term and short term memory, as well as the impor tance of ordering your information 
effectively. As UX designers, when applying the serial position effect, it is critical to empower the 
user by providing task relevant information on the screen where possible, sharing concise 
prompts or cues, reducing the level of recall needed across the user journey, and highlighting

overwhelmed with infor mation. They should be able to navigate every aspect of your interfaces 
or landing pages intuitively, with little additional thought, while understanding what to do next

275 Information foraging  
Information Forging is a theory that applies the ideas from optimal foraging theory to understand how 
human users search for information. The theory assumes that, when searching for information, 
humans use "built in" foraging mechanisms that evolved to help our animal ancestors find food. Importantly, better understanding of human search behavior can improve the usability of websites or 
any other user interface. The Background: In the 1970s optimal foraging theory was developed 
by anthropologists and ecologists to explain how animals hunt for food. It suggested that the eating 
habits of animals revolve around maximizing energy intake over a given amount of time. For 
every predator, certain prey is worth pursuing, while others would result in a net loss of energy. In the early 1990s, Peter Pirolli and Stuart Card from PARC noticed the similarities between users' 
information searching patterns and animal food foraging strategies. Working together 
with psychologists to analyze users' actions and the information landscape that they navigated (links, 
descriptions, and other data), they showed that information seekers use the same strategies as food 
foragers. In the late 1990s, Ed H. Chi worked with Pirolli, Card and others at PARC to further develop 
information scent ideas and algorithms to actually use these concepts in real interactive systems, 
including the modeling of web user browsing behavior, the inference of information needs from web 
visit log files, and the use of information scent concepts in reading and browsing interfaces. Details of the theory 
Definition of informavore from Wikipedia. The term informavore (also spelled informivore ) 
characterizes an organism that consumes information. It is meant to be a description of human 
behavior in modern information society, in comparison to omnivore, as a description of humans 
consuming food. George A.

Miller coined the term in 198 3 as an analogy to how organisms 
survive by consuming negative entropy (as suggested by Erwin Schrödinger). Miller states, 
276 "Just as the body survives by ingesting negative entropy, so the m ind survives by ingesting 
information. In a very general sense, all higher organisms are informavores ." 
An early use of the term was in a newspaper article by Jonathan Chevreau[3] where he quotes a 
speech made by Zenon Pylyshyn. Soon after, the term appeared in the introduction of 
Pylyshyn's seminal book on Cognitive Science, Computation and Cognition . More recently the term has been popularized by philosopher Daniel Dennett in his book Kinds of 
Minds and by cognitive scientist Steven Pinker. "Informavores " constantly make decisions on what kind of information to look for, wh ether to 
stay at the current site to try to find additional information or whether they should move on to 
another site, which path or link to follow to the next information site, and when to finally stop the 
search. Although human cognition is not a result of evolutionary pressure to improve Web use, 
survival related traits to respond quickly on partial information and reduce energy expenditures 
force them to optimise their searching behavior and, simultaneously, to minimize the thinking 
required. 
277 Informati on scent 
The most important concept in the information foraging theory is information scent .[1][2] As 
animals rely on scents to indicate the chances of finding prey in current area and guide them to 
other promising patches, so do humans rely on various cues in the info rmation environment to 
get similar answers. Human users estimate how much useful information they are likely to get 
on a given path, and after seeking information compare the actual outcome with their 
predictions. When the information scent stops getting s tronger (i.e., when users no longer 
expect to find useful additional information), the users move to a different information source. Information diets 
Some tendencies in the behavior of web users are easily understood from the information foraging 
theory s tandpoint. On the Web, each site is a patch and information is the prey. Leaving a site is 
easy but finding good sites has not always been as easy. Advanced search engines have changed 
this fact by reliably providing relevant links, altering the foraging s trategies of the users. When users 
expect that sites with lots of information are easy to find, they have less incentive to stay in one 
place. The growing availability of broadband connections may have a similar effect: always on 
connections encourage this behavior, short online visits to get specific answers. Models 
Attempts have been made to develop computational cognitive models to characterize information 
foraging behavior on the Web. These models assume that users perceive relevance of information 
base d on some measures of information scent, which are usually derived based on statistical 
techniques that extract semantic relatedness of words from large text databases. Recently these 
information foraging modelled have been extended to explain social infor mation behavior. See 
also models of collaborative tagging in Wikipedia to learn more details of collaborative tagging . 
278 Chapter 13: User Personas 
What are user personas for and why should we use them? Where do we start when creating 
one? Who are we designing our products for again? No one has all the sure fire answers to 
designing a wildly successful product, but there are methods out there that are more likely to 
help you do it. One of those methods includes knowing who you are designing for in the first 
place by creating user personas. This will explore how user personas can act as a design compass while using your wireframe 
tool, along with the steps for creating one. You will also find some great tools to put quickly and 
easily one together! What is a user persona? The user persona was developed back in the nineties to gain powerful insights into a products 
target audience and the users habits and preferences. It continues to be used today by UX 
design teams and marketing depa rtments across the world. The purpose of personas is to create reliable and realistic representations of your key audience 
segments for reference. These representations should be based on qualitative and some 
quantitative user research and web analytics . Remember, your personas are only as good as 
the research behind them.

Effecti ve personas: 
Represent a major user group for your website 
Express and focus on the major needs and expectations of the most important user 
groups 
Give a clear picture of the user's expectations and how they're likely to use the site 
Aid in uncovering univ ersal features and functionality 
Describe real people with backgrounds, goals, and values 
279 Benefits of Personas 
Personas help to focus decisions surrounding site components by adding a layer of 
realworld consideration to the conversation. They also offer a quick and inexpensive 
way to test and prioritize those features throughout the development process. In 
additio n they can help: 
Stakeholders and leaders evaluate new site feature ideas 
Information architects develop informed wireframes, interface behaviors, and labeling 
Designers create the overall look and feel of the website 
System engineers/developers decide whi ch approaches to take based on user 
behaviors 
Copy writers ensure site content is written to the appropriate audiences 
Best Practices for Developing Personas 
Personas development belongs at the beginning of the project, as personas can inform 
site functionality, help uncover gaps, or highlight new opportunities. You may develop one or more personas for a project but limit yourself to the main 
audiences for the site. Fo r any given project, creating only three or four personas is 
best. Remember that it is better to paint with a broad brush and meet the needs of the 
larger populations than try to meet the needs of everyone. The goal of personas is not 
represent all audienc es or address all needs of the website but instead to focus on the 
major needs of the most important user groups. 
280 To ensure your personas are accurate representations of your users and have the 
support of your stakeholders throughout the process, you shoul d: 
Conduct user research : Answer the following questions: Who are your users and 
why are they using the system? What behaviors, assumptions, and expectations 
color their view of the system? Condense the research : Look for themes/characteristics that are specific, relevant, 
and universal to the system and its users. Brainstorm : Organize elements into persona groups that represent your target 
users. Name or classify each group. Refine : Combine and prioritize the rough personas. Separate them into primary, 
secondary, and, if necessary, complementary categories. You should have roughly 
35 personas and their identified characteristics. Make them realistic : Develop the appropriate descripti ons of each personas 
background, motivations, and expectations. Do not include a lot of personal 
information. Be relevant and serious; humor is not appropriate. Questions to Ask During Persona Development

287 User personas are a representation of your app or websites user base segments. They function 
as a benchmark for design and teams to work with to create the optimal user experience. It is a 
fictitious profile based on the type of people who would be the ma in users of your app. The structure of a user persona 
The user persona normally consists of both a fictional name and a picture of the person. This is 
followed by a short bio, along with a description of their age, gender, occupation, hobbies, likes 
and di slikes, which are non fictional and based on real aggregated data . How a user persona works 
Knowing your users makes it easier to rem ember who youre designing for, as the users of other 
products might not be the users of your own. User personas turn the user into an actual 
person you can get to know and conceptualize. Hanging user persona profiles on the office wall or notice board, uploading them to your UX 
research tools or sending them as PDF for PP files to your colleagues to refer back to every 
time they design a new feature helps keep your product on track. This is because a user persona turns the abstract concept of the user into a person with 
thoughts, feelings and emotions. 
288 
This person represents a group of users who share similar characteristics and goals. These 
goals will dictate the best design patter ns for your website or app to provide the best user 
experience.

It will also dictate how best to solve certain design problems. Even when it comes to simple updates – being on the same page as the user can prevent 
backlashes against updates, such as the unwanted change Instagram made in 2018 when 
vastly altered their users e xperience by replacing vertical scrolling with horizontal. Even when it 
comes to designing enterprise software, user personas can provide invaluable insights for 
creating smooth user flows, something that until recently, many companies have ignored in 
favor of price.
